animal.description:
Smudge / Female / 2 Years / 70 lbs / Great Pyrenees Mix / Brampton

Meet Smudge! Despite her size, Smudge fancies herself a bit of a lap dog! She will snuggle her nose into your armpit or under your hand to ask for love. Her fosters describe her as “a super sweet and loving soul.” She is gentle, affectionate, cuddly, goofy, well mannered and protective. She loves walks and running, but is also the resident nap queen and couch potato. All she wants is to be near her people, and bonds closely with her family.

When her family comes home Smudge is very excited, and may even try and go in for a hug. With new people she may wag her tail but is shy at first. Generally she will look to her trusted humans for approval before going ahead for a sniff. Once she builds a bond with someone she relies on them for encouragement, safety and love. Smudge has been tested with children and she does amazing. She will do best with dog savvy children who understand the basics of dog body language and when she needs a break.

When she is left alone she is crated and settles quickly. She is also crated at night and may whine for a few minutes before settling. Overall she is a very good girl and could likely be trusted with free reign. With adequate opportunities to use the washroom, she is fully potty trained.

Currently Smudge is getting three walks a day, plus additional time to play in the backyard. Her favorite thing is to run freely and get silly in a secured space. She is amazing on leash and doesn’t pull unless she wants to smell something or go potty. When crossing busy streets she does get scared so she needs gentle encouragement to continue. She is afraid of cars when they pass and get stressed during car rides. Building her confidence surrounding vehicles will be an ongoing part of her journey.

In her foster home, Smudge has been kept off of furniture. She learns house rules quickly and always respects them. Smudge’s greatest joy in life is making her family proud! She is smart and has already learned sit, paw, down, come, leave it, recall and is working on stay.

Smudge’s ideal family would be a house with a fully fenced backyard. She may be able to adapt to a large apartment, as long as her exercise needs are met. Due to her anxieties with traffic and cars, she would prefer homes in the suburbs or quiet country. Smudge does well with all other dogs, but has not been tested with cats.

If you’re interested in adopting Smudge please apply at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/adoption-info#adoption-form

Smudge’s adoption fee is $800. To learn more about our adoption fees and the adoption process, please visit our FAQs at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/about-us#about-faqs.

APPLICATION REQUIRED from www.dashdog.org
Adoption Fee $350

***We don't know how to make this more clear: OUR APPLICATION IS NOT THE PETFINDER APP; OUR APPLICATION IS ON www.dashdog.org. PLEASE complete OUR application if you are interested in meeting our dogs or puppies! Without OUR application being completed, you WILL NOT be considered or receive any communication from us. Thank You!

***AND our listed dogs ARE READY IMMEDIATELY; we only meet with families WHO ARE READY TO ADOPT! IF YOU APPLY and WE APPROVE YOU it means we are assuming when you meet any of our dogs and fall in love you're ready to ADOPT AND TAKE HIM OR HER HOME!

APPLICATION REQUIRED from www.dashdog.org Adoption Fee $350 - the fee is NON-NEGOTIABLE and is not specific for any dog or puppy; it goes to the expenses of the organization as a whole*
OUR APPLICATION IS ON www.dashdog.org and must be completed in order to set up a meeting.
Our listed dogs ARE READY IMMEDIATELY; we only meet with families WHO ARE READY TO ADOPT! IF YOU APPLY and if WE APPROVE YOU it means we are assuming when you meet any of our dogs and fall in love you're ready to ADOPT AND HIM OR HER HOME!

Meet NICO!
This beautiful purebred Aussie male is just 10 months old - he is a typical young Aussie who can wrestle and play with other large dogs or cuddle and lie calmly with his favorite humans.
Nico was originally adopted from DASH at 10 weeks old - but his adoptive family sadly had to return him because they felt they weren't the right household for Nico's life; as a herding dog he was occasionally apt to run and play with kids but at 4/5/6 months old he began to "nip," a common trait since he is a herding dog but one requires consistency and cooperation in re-training.
Nico's family has reiterated that he is not a mean or aggressive dog, the return is "because of them, not Nico." We asked them to call our trainer at our expense if they wanted to work with him but ultimately we all agreed their kids were too young and Nico will be better off in a more herding breed-experienced home.
In the the week since Nico came to my house he has been a model dog. He is friendly, cuddly, obedient, house trained and definitely deserves to get into a Forever home.
Nico plays GREAT with similar sized or larger dogs. He is also very mellow and laid-back, doesn't demand attention 24/7 and loves outdoor walks as much as indoor cuddling! He actually has very moderate energy for an Aussie ~ his former owner told me she is sure their home was "too chaotic" for Nico and is happy to hear he is enjoying his new temporary life.
Nico is full-grown at 55 lbs; he knows basic commands and is eager to please. He is happy, confident, definitely needs to decompress in his "new forever" environment. Since HE is only a baby/puppy. we are looking for a home without human kiddos so he can be the baby for awhile!
He would also be a great companion, jogging partner, snuggle-buddy and co-pilot for a single person or couple with time, love and attention to give him.
If you're interested and meeting Nico for adoption please complete our application on www.dashdog.org Then, TEXT SARA; I have has Nico at my house!
General Info - PLEASE READ! *Our $350 adoption fee is based on the cost of rescuing, transporting and vetting each dog; we do not try to compete on prices with municipal shelters whose funds are paid by the city. Our philosophy is to rescue highly adoptable dogs, have them live kennel-free in private homes for temperament assessments and individual personalities.
We work hard to match EACH dog with the right family - kids or no kids, other dogs male or female and/or cats. With very rare exceptions all dogs over 6 months will be spayed or neutered PRIOR to adoption - dogs under 6 months will include a spay/neuter date AND referral info for lower-cost surgery if the adopter does not choose to use her or his personal vet. OUR VETS WILL NOT PERFORM SPAY NEUTER SURGERIES UNTIL DOG IS 6 MONTHS OLD.

Please READ ALL of our info below BEFORE SENDING APPLICATION.

Our goal is to help our puppies and dogs find FOREVER HOMES AND FAMILIES, NOT TO MAKE IT PROHIBITIVE FOR YOU TO ADOPT. However, once we review the application and contact you, we MEET TO ADOPT, so please let us know if you are ONLY APPLYING TO STAY ON FILE or THAT YOU ARE READY TO ADOPT, for the consideration of our puppies and dogs and families who know the time is right!

animal.description:
Meet Gerald! Gerald is a Very Important Pup here at Charleston Animal Society!

In the beginning of December, we took in a transfer of 15 dogs (Including Gerald) from the Bahamas. All of these dogs have displayed under socialized and fearful behavior. From this transfer there are four dogs left. We are looking for a patient adopter who has a background in handling a dog with these types of anxieties and who can create a safe environment. This adopter has to understand these dogs can be a flight risk, they are sensitive to noises and hesitant to approach people. They are also looking for a home with a confident helper dog. Any potential adopter willing to open their home and hearts to any of these four dogs please reach out to the Charleston Animal Society Behavior Team to set up a meet and greet. (843) 327-1527 or behavior@charlestonanimalsociety.org

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
=========================================================

Please contact
app@aarfhouston.org
for more information about this dog. You can apply online by clicking on Application .

Puppies
that are under 4 months old cannot be adopted outside of our Veterinary Service area. Please call for specific locations.

Children under 8 years old
often are not a good match for our puppies and dogs. In order to protect both, your child and our rescued dogs/puppies from harm, we seldom if ever adopt to families with young children.

Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet at one of our adoption events. Thank you for considering a rescue!

The adoption fee includes vaccinations, Bordetella, de-worming, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip. There is a an additional $12.99 fee for Home Again for a lifetime registration of the microchip.
Puppies cannot be adopted outside of the Houston area until they are spay/neutered after they are 4 months old. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.
NOTE: In our bios, we provide information based on our volunteer's experience with a particular dog; such as temperament, training, and ability to get along with others.
AARF is a 501(c)3 Non Profit, all breed, no kill organization. Our group is always in need of donations in order to continue to give the needed medical care to our rescues. Adoption fees do not begin to cover all of the medical costs. Any donation , no matter how small is a big help and is greatly appreciated. Please help us to continue to help them. Thank you.

animal.description:
Hello!! My name is Dover. I am a one year old pointer mix being fostered in Chippewa falls, WI. This is actually my second time with my foster family so my mom is going to make me be a little more specific about the kind of family that I need ? So I am a very active boy. I need another youngish (or older active) dog to play with. No exceptions. I get along with all the dogs that I've met. So far so good? Ok. I also can be a bit jumpy so kids over say 5 might be best. I just would hate to knock anyone over. The 6 kids in my house keep me busy and I LOVE to run with my dad. He says I do really well. I can go 6 miles!! Let's talk about those frisky felines. They are everywhere in this house! The ones that ignore me are awesome. But the ones that get all hissy and up in my face - well I like to bark at them and try to play because what are they doing?! I've never hurt a cat though. Just something to keep in mind. I am potty trained and sleep well in my kennel. Oh and I'm up to date on all of my shots plus I'm fixed! Juuuust one more thing. I really like just MY family in MY house. I tend to bark aggressively at strangers and my mom has to put me in my kennel. This is something I'm not proud of and I definitely will need to work on. Outside of my house say on a walk I'm hesitant about strangers but I warm up.  Phew. That part was hard to say but it's good to be honest up front. I am a lover though. I am so soft and my family calls me butter boy. I love them but I need to find my forever home. Is it you? My adoption fee is $300. Please apply at www.lastpawrescue.org ask for Dover!
501(c) approved Wisconsin Agriculture License # 285589-DS

NEBULA ~ spayed Husky mix, 1 year, 37 lbs

Hi, I’m Nebula,  I’m a little shy until I get comfortable with you, but then you will be my person.  I get along great with all other dogs and love people off all ages and sizes once I know they will be kind to me.  One way to help me learn that, and anything really, is with treas.  I love treats!! So if you have a bag of biscuits and want to make a new friend – come see me.

If you are interested in meeting me, please contact us at DOGS@SAVINGPAWS.COM to set up an appointment.  All of our dogs are in foster homes so you will need to schedule an appointment to come meet the dog/puppy. We require approved applications to adopt an animal through Saving Paws Animal Rescue, Inc., so please serious inquiries only. We are a volunteer run animal rescue so please allow us time to get back to you for an appointment. Our applications can be found on our website at www.savingpaws.com 

Adoption fees include; Spay/Neuter, Micro-chipped, age appropriate vaccines including distemper, bordatella and if old enough rabies vaccines, dewormed, heartworm tested(if old enough)

We are always in need of foster homes, so if you are interested in opening your home and heart to an animal in need until they find their furever homes, please  email dogs@savingpaws.com.
Saving Paws Animal Rescue Inc. is a no-kill animal welfare nonprofit organization dedicated to saving homeless, abandoned and special needs pets. Please consider making a donation on our Web site, www.savingpaws.com - every donation, no matter how small, helps us save lives.

animal.description:
I know what you’re probably thinking... who is this dreamy guy with the big ol’ meathead? Meet Meatloaf! This happy, smiling, young man is estimated to be about 1.5 years old. His breed is our best guess based off his physical attributes. We can’t say enough good things about this dog! For spending 6 months in a rural shelter before we pulled him into our organization, he’s pretty awesome. Willing to learn and treat motivated makes molding him into the perfect dog a breeze! He’ll do just about anything for a meaty treat or squeaky ball, will gladly play fetch till your arm falls off. But afterwards is ready for a good snuggle and nap! He already knows the commands for sit, down, and shake and can catch and toy or treat you throw his way! He has the build of a true athlete and is a strong, solid build. Leash manners are a work in process. He has excellent house manners and hasn’t offered to lift a leg in his foster home and he doesn’t use the furniture like a jungle gym either. Despite his size, he thinks he belongs in your lap giving you kisses while you scratch his rump. He’s a truly ladies man and can be slower to warm up to men but if they properly greet him with a hotdog, he’s cool. He lives with two cats in his foster home and will follow them if they run around but is easily called off and harmless. He also is coexisting peacefully with the female dog in his foster home. With some continued obedience and a firm handler, Meatloaf will be the most loyal companion to his family!

He has been neutered, microchipped, vaccinated and heartworm tested. His ideal home would be with older children as he doesn’t realize his size and one with a fenced in yard. If you’d like to add this young and handsome bachelor to your home please fill out an application at: https://forms.gle/WkiD5PgdmfjUTteF9

animal.description:
Meet Morty, this sweet guy was surrendered to us with Lucy after they lost their person. While Lucy and Morty are great friends and love to hangout, they aren't bonded and don't have to be adopted together, but they wouldn't mind it either!  (check out Lucy's bio too!) Morty is a great example of why Black Labs are so great. He is a quiet, calmer guy, who can still be playful. A true gentleman he will wait his turn to go through the doorway, and he isn't even really interested in getting on the furniture, even though we've asked!

This guy is a bit overweight at 100lbs, the vet would like to see him around 90. He definitely is a gentle giant, he will gladly share his bowl and walk away with food left in it. Outside he enjoys chasing a ball or rolling and galloping through the snow. He would probably enjoy a yard to take ownership of, and we'll bet he will love sunbathing in the summer! 

Morty does fine with other dogs and has not been cat tested. This guy would need a friend to have at home or an owner who is home most of the time. He is house trained and around 7 years old.

Morty is UTD on all vaccines and preventative, neutered, and microchipped.

Morty's adoption fee is $250, and adopters must live within 175 miles of the Quad City Area.

If interested in meeting Morty you must fill out the online application at www.k9kindnessrescue.org/adopt/application

Morty and K9 Kindness Rescue thank you for considering adoption through rescue for your new family companion!

animal.description:
Peggy / Female / Approx. 5 Years / 24 lbs / Street Mix / Toronto

**Peggy has seizures that are being managed by daily medication. The current cost for medication to keep her stable is $365 per month. This will be an ongoing issue throughout her life but she is doing well with consistent veterinary care. She will need blood work every 6 months and it is recommended her adopters keep a seizure journal to track her episodes. Any potential adopters can speak to our vet team directly to better understand her needs**

Meet Peggy! Peggy was pulled from a shelter living in very poor conditions. Unfortunately the facility didn’t have the resources to support its residents and left them tied up outside. Thankfully our partners in Mexico stepped up and took as many as they could support at the time. After a full meal and some much needed care, Peggy made the trip to Canada in search of her forever home!

Peggy is described as friendly, laid back, affectionate, cuddly, smart and loving. Everyone who meets her remarks on how happy she is and that her tail is always wagging. She’s not much for toys yet but she sure does love her walks! Peggy is in heaven when she gets her paws massaged. She is eager to please her people and will make an excellent addition to a family who understand her specific needs.

Peggy is a social butterfly and happy to meet all people. She will be the first at the door with a happy smile, welcoming anyone into her home. she has not had much exposure to children but likely would do well with humans of all sizes!

So far Peggy hasn’t been left alone much, but has been tested up to four hours. She hasn’t shown any signs of seperation anxiety but is always happy when her family comes home. She is definitely a little escape artist so all doors must be secured at all times. Any access to the backyard should be monitored and leashed if there is any risk of her getting loose.

Peggy has done well with training in all areas and has adapted beautifully to life as a pet. She already knows sit, stay, paw, no and come! She will need ongoing support on leash training as she can be very reactive to squirrels. Due to her desire to chase small animals we think she would do best in a cat-free home. She does well with other well adjusted canine siblings!

Peggy’s ideal home would be a house with a fully fenced backyard. She drinks a lot of water due to her medication so needs frequent bathroom breaks throughout the day. She loves her walks and would do well in the city (or suburbs) as she has not expressed any fears to noises. She loves being with her family and would prefer they are home more often than not. Most importantly her family needs to have a solid understanding of her medical needs and be able to support her through them (see special needs).

If you’re interested in adopting Peggy, please apply at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/adoption-info#adoption-form

Peggy’s adoption fee is $800. To learn more about our adoption fees and the adoption process, please visit our FAQs at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/about-us#about-faqs.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Shepherd | 6 yrs. old | 67 lbs. | Adoption Fee: $425.00
Hello there, I'm Xenia. I'm searching for my forever family to give me the good life, inclusive of lots of pets and unlimited snuggles! One of my favorite hobbies is snuggling into blankets and rolling on pillows and cushions. I also love to go on walks and am very good on the leash! I don't pull, and I wait patiently for my human. I move a little bit slower, so I wouldn't mind having an older human to guide me on my walks! After a nice, ambling stroll I love to take a good snooze. I'm very good at napping, and also sleep through the night. When I stand up from my nap you'll hear me groan a little bit, but I'm just letting you know how good it feels to stretch out my joints, and I get around just fine. I won't get up on any of your furniture because I prefer to nap on the ground on a soft blanket. I love being around my foster family and do well with my foster dog brother, but he is significantly younger and has "puppy energy", and I'd prefer that my forever family be more slow paced and relaxed. I am not interested in friends of the feline persuasion, no cats for me! I hope that my forever family will have lots of squeaky toys. I will provide a ton of laughs with my squeaky toy antics, I love to play with them and toss them around! I am 100% potty trained, and know basic commands like "sit" and "come". I'm food motivated and my foster mom says that I'm a little bit too good of an eater, so I'm working on slimming down just a little. Are you looking for a gentle, loving forever friend? If so, I'm your gal! Submit your application today!

Completion of an Adoption Application via our website (www.RescueCrew.org) is the best way to show your interest in an animal and is the first step in the adoption process.

All companion animals adopted by The Rescue Crew are spayed/neutered, up-to-date on age appropriate vaccinations, tested for FIV/FeLK (cats) or heartworm (dogs), microchipped, dewormed and provided with monthly flea/tick and heartworm preventatives.

The Rescue Crew is a foster based rescue organization, meaning all of our adoptable pets are located in homes throughout Minnesota. We do not have a physical location where you can stop by to visit the animals - we require the completion of an Adoption Application prior to meeting any of our adoptable pets in foster care.

For the most complete information regarding this animal, and all of our adoptable pets, please ensure you are visiting our website directly at www.RescueCrew.org. You can also access the necessary online adoption application here as well.

animal.description:
Please contact Pet (information@pethelpersinc.org) for more information about this pet.

This handsome guy is Brody. Brody is only 2 years old and he has Tarsal Osteochondrosis. Kind of like arthritis from what we understand. We were told by one of the best bone doctors around that even with surgery it won't help long term. He is currently getting treats daily to help with hips and joints. Brody weighs about 65lbs. He will need a home without stairs. Brody would do best as an only dog. He does ok with most dogs but can be testy at times if he is resting on his bed. He also would be best in a home with no kids. Brody is honestly a big goofball. He does try to run and play some. But for the most part he is very chill. He really deserves a loving home where he can relax and just be loved. Exercise is good whether it be going for walks or a fenced yard for him to walk or run around in. For whoever adopts him we will have hip and joint treats sent to you for life. He just really deserves someone who will have patience and be kind to this darling boy. He is crate trained and housebroke. Brody is neutered, utd on shots, wormed and microchipped. If you think you can give him that wonderful loving home he so deserves... please fill out an application at

https://www.pethelpersinc.org/adoption-application/

He is adoption fee is 150.00 and he is being fostered in Clarksburg WV
For more information on this animal email adoptionisforever@pethelpersinc.org.

Pet Helpers is a 501(c)(3) nonprofit foster based volunteer rescue located in Fairmont, WV. We do adopt out of state to approved applicants, if you are willing to drive to WV to pick up your pet. We do not fly or use transport companies. Our adoption fee is $150.00 for mixed breed puppies and adult dogs, $225.00 for full blooded puppies and adult dogs and $50.00 for cats and kittens. Regardless if the animal is a mixed breed or full blooded they are spayed/neutered prior to adoption IF they are old enough. If they are too young at the time of adoption, then it is your financial responsibility to spay/neuter the pet by the age of 6 months and you must provide proof for our files that it has been done. All of our pets are checked by a vet, given the shots appropriate for their age and any other treatment deemed necessary by the vet. All of our pets are adopted as indoor pets and are not be outdoors tied to a box 24/7. The pet you are adopting has been living in a home with a foster family. You are expected to take possession of the pet you are applying for within a few days of application approval. This will enable us to accept another pet into that home. Because we are a rescue, and believe that spaying and neutering is crucial in stopping the reproduction of unwanted puppies/kittens and massive amounts of animals dying daily in shelters across the country, we expect any animal already in your home to be spayed/neutered. If for any reason you are unable to keep the pet you have adopted you are required to return them to Pet Helpers, Inc. They are not to be sold or given away.

Check us out on Facebook!!!!!! We hope you will give us two paws up, like our page and share with your friends. Pet Helpers, Inc.

animal.description:
Indy is a sweet and calm dog with nice manners. He is curious and interested in new sights and sounds when out and about. His little nub is always wagging! Balls are his favorite thing, and he loves to snuggle as well. We think he would do great with children 7 and up. He is totally house trained.

With our trainer, Indy was happy to trade toys for a small treat and quickly began to respond to a Drop command. He is resistant to the crate so we are taking it slow. Indy knows Sit, but is still learning to do it around distractions. He responds well to slip lead pressure on walks.

He used to live with a mini schnauzer and had no issues there. He has also met other dogs while out and about with his foster mom and has done well, though he can be overwhelming with little dogs. However, he also has a history of dog selectivity so any introductions should go slowly.

THE MARVELOUS MISS MARLEE is ready for a new home! She and her sister/littermate were going to be surrendered at a shelter because their young family has lost their house due to Covid.
Marlee is a BEAUTIFUL, cuddly and sensitive Big Baby Puppy who has lived with young children and who loves other dogs. She and her sister (adopted last night) were not great together; the rescuer who knew the situation agreed that the stress in the house was a factor.
I'd love a male dog-companion for Marlee. I've been watching her wrestle with Nico, a male Aussie also being listed, the past two hours; they both finally flopped down next to each other on the patio and are snoozing in the sun.u
Marlee has a very mild-moderate energy level. She acclimated to our environment - which is 2 pulses above a Flatline with no problem at all. She is happy to cuddle and just hang out. She'll be a wonderful fur-friend/companion & support dog for someone or a great family pet.
General Info - PLEASE READ! *Our $350 adoption fee is based on the cost of rescuing, transporting and vetting each dog; we do not try to compete on prices with municipal shelters whose funds are paid by the city. Our philosophy is to rescue highly adoptable dogs, have them live kennel-free in private homes for temperament assessments and individual personalities.
We work hard to match EACH dog with the right family - kids or no kids, other dogs male or female and/or cats. With very rare exceptions all dogs over 6 months will be spayed or neutered PRIOR to adoption - dogs under 6 months will include a spay/neuter date AND referral info for lower-cost surgery if the adopter does not choose to use her or his personal vet. OUR VETS WILL NOT PERFORM SPAY NEUTER SURGERIES UNTIL DOG IS 6 MONTHS OLD.

Please READ ALL of our info below BEFORE SENDING APPLICATION.

Our goal is to help our puppies and dogs find FOREVER HOMES AND FAMILIES, NOT TO MAKE IT PROHIBITIVE FOR YOU TO ADOPT. However, once we review the application and contact you, we MEET TO ADOPT, so please let us know if you are ONLY APPLYING TO STAY ON FILE or THAT YOU ARE READY TO ADOPT, for the consideration of our puppies and dogs and families who know the time is right!

Im a cute little Beagle/mix, emphasis on the MIX! I definitely have a beagle-y bark and face, but Im pretty tall and skinny too. Your basic one-of-a-kind rescue pup.
I am 3 years old and 20 pounds! A perfect age and size, if you ask me. I can be a little shy around new people, but oh boy, do I warm up quick. Ill be right in your lap before you know it! I bond quickly and wont want you to leave might even let you know with a few barks. 
I dont play with toys much and dont know too many commands pretty much all I need is a human to love and a comfy place to sleep. I enjoy being petted once were acquainted, and I walk nicely on a leash but can be a little timid at times.
I super enjoy coexisting with other pups. Im not much of a player just yet but hanging around with other canines makes me happy.
Im a cute little guy who cant wait to be a part of your family! A little time to warm up is all I need, and youll soon see how sweet I can be!
All my love,
GB

animal.description:
Meet Marvelous Molly Moo!

Molly is in an IDOG foster home in Bellaire, TX near Houston. Please read ALL the information in her listing before applying for her. If you would like to be considered as a potential adopter for her, please complete our adoption application at http://www.idogrescue.com/adoption_application (copy/paste the URL into your browser). If you have completed an application in the last 3 months and meet the requirements for his new home, you can email us at rescue@idogrescue.com and let us know you are interested in Molly.

*AGE: 9 years old (born October 2011)

*WEIGHT: 118 lbs. – she is on a diet and exercise plan and should weigh 100 lbs. or a bit less

*FENCE REQUIREMENT: A physical secure fence is required. No electronic fence or e-collar will be allowed as we feel this would not set her up for success.

*COAT TYPE: very soft wavy low-shedding coat; she is currently shaved down due to matting when she came in to IDOG. Her new family should be prepared to brush his coat regularly and have her groomed every few months. This is approximately $100 per groom.

*ENERGY LEVEL: moderate to low energy. She would love to be your BFF, your Zoom buddy and your cooking friend. She would also love to be your exercise coach and diet partner.  She loves to go for walk, play fetch and is always up for jumping in the car for some fun.

*DOGS: she LOVES other dogs and has lived with large and medium dogs in her foster home. We feel she would do well in a home with another dog.

*CATS: Her previous owner said she chased cats and could accidentally hurt them. She has a high prey drive.

*KIDS: Molly LOVES everyone and we think she’d be great with people of all ages. However, she doesn’t realize her size and does jump up to say hi so any children in the home should be OK with that.

*CAR: LOVES going for a ride!

*CRATE: she hasn’t been crated in her foster home and does fine. She does whine when she is left alone.

*HOUSE TRAINED: Yes!

*LEASH: Molly LOVES to walk and walks well on a leash. Given her large size we use a harness to allow for more control in the case she sees a squirrel!
Here's what Molly-Moo’s foster parents had to say about her:

Marvelous Molly Moo is an uber sweet 9 year old Labradoodle who was initially found as a stray in Houston. Her owner found us and made the hard decision to surrender Molly to our care due to the owner’s declining health. She wanted us to find Molly a wonderful new home and that is what we will do!

Want an exercise partner and Zoom buddy? How about a shotgun rider? She will be your immediate BFF! Molly is a happy soul and ALWAYS greets you with a wagging tail  – whether you’ve been away for 5 seconds or 3 hours. She is like the BFF you have that always make you feel so special because you ARE special to her. She radiates unconditional love and such as easy girl to be around.

Molly LOVES to GO! 
-she is the first out the door to go play in backyard, 
-she is the first one leashed up to go for a walk and 
-she is the first to jump in the car to go for a ride. She jumps up in joy when knows going for a walk. 

Molly LOVES…everything and everyone:
-she loves people – she would love to be with a family where someone is home frequently as she cries when she is left alone.
-she loves other dogs – she would love to have a buddy to sleep next to and to play with and to go for walks with.
-she loves helping – whether that be next to you while you Zoom from home or clean – she’s your side-kick.
-she loves eating – she would love to help you cook and will help clean up any food you accidentally drop on the floor. She is doing well on her restricted diet and is rapidly losing the unneeded weight.
-she loves going for a ride – she’s the first one in!
-she loves walking – she is the first one leashed and jumps up and down when she realizes it’s walk time.

Molly is a grown-up girl and can be trusted to roam the house and not chew anything she isn’t supposed to. She has great house manners. She is very food-motivated and will do anything for a treat. She LOVES to be petted and will lean into you for affection. She just fits right in to your house. Molly would much rather be with her people than by herself and whines when she is left alone. She would do best with someone who is home frequently and a home with another dog to hang out with. 

Molly likes squeaky balls  and will chase after them – kind of like her own game of fetch. She is a sweetheart and LOVES everyone. She wants to be right next to you and is very affectionate. Molly needs to lose some lbs. and loves to walk so the weight is already coming off quickly! 

She recently had surgery to remove a growth on her nose and one on her head – both were benign. We did extensive testing prior to surgery and everything was normal. 

Molly is spayed, up to date on vaccines, microchipped, and house trained. She just had a dental cleaning. She has cataracts which are not impeding her vision much. She sometimes needs help seeing to go outside to potty in the dark. She is heartworm and fecal negative and on heartworm/flea and tick preventatives.

ADOPTION FEE: $100

OUR ADOPTION PROCESS

We will review your application and let you know if you made our short list of applicants. We base our adoption decisions on what is in the best interest of our dogs. Please note our adoption policies are in place for the safety and welfare of our dogs - your understanding is appreciated.

We are all volunteers and have jobs, families, pets of our own to care for - we do the best that we can to get back to you in a timely manner. We believe in taking time to go through our thorough process to try to match the dog with the best fit for that dog.

Our adoption process may take 2-4 weeks.

• You must be approved to adopt before we will schedule a meet and greet.
• We expect approved adopters to visit Molly in her foster home within a short period of time of being approved to adopt her.
• Our adoption process involves vet and personal reference checks, phone interviews, a home visit, an adoption contract and an adoption fee.OUR 

ADOPTION FEES RANGE FROM $100 - $750 depending on the dog. The following is a general guide, but each dog is assessed individually. It currently costs IDOG an average of over $400 for basic vet, grooming, and foster care on each dog; that does not allow for the ones who get sick, need surgery, have special needs, or are heartworm positive.

ADOPTION FEES:
Under 6 months $550 and up
6 months to 2 years $450 and up
2 years - 4 years $350 and up
4 years + $100 and up
Special Needs fee/donation assessed on individual basis

TO APPLY FOR MOLLY, PLEASE COMPLETE THE APPLICATION ON OUR WEBSITE:
http://www.idogrescue.com/adoption_application

animal.description:
Reilly needs your help to find the right home!

This handsome tall lanky 5 year old is a loving loyal devoted companion to his person, but can be nervous with new people and protective of his toys and resources and needs an adult only home preferably with just one woman he can devote himself to. He was originally abandoned outside our shelter 4 years ago and adopted to a wonderful family, but sadly due to the arrival of a new baby, his current home is no longer a match for his needs. 

Reilly is an active boy who would be a great hiking companion and has endless energy. He is currently living with a larger female dog who he loves to play with although since he doesn't share toys well he may be best living as an only pet. We see some Pyrenees, catahoula, Aussie, maybe even some Great Dane in his mix. Though he is large he is a gentle soul for the most part and needs the right person to work with and manage his resource guarding (don't take anything out of his mouth, but he will "trade" for a higher value treat. 

Reilly is still residing with his family to avoid a shelter stay, but has to stay mostly separated for everyone's safety and not able to get as much attention and exercise as he would like and is hoping to find the right home soon. Please submit an application so we can set up an appointment to meet this handsome fellow!

animal.description:
Meet Henny Penny!  

Penny girl came to us looking a little ragged and rough.  After ending up in the shelter as a stray for a second time, her owners decided they no longer wanted her in the condition she was in.  Her skin was a mess and her fur had become patchy and dry.  She was thin and needed some major TLC.  From what we can tell, she had been running the streets for some time and we are just happy we found her when we did. 

Penny is 50 lbs and is estimated to be 2-3 years old.  She is as sweet as can be! and is such a snuggle bug! You will never find her far from her people!

 She has been living in a foster home with 3 older gentlemen dogs and doing very well.  She still has quite a bit of energy and spunk in her but she takes corrections well and knows when to back off.  She is very playful, loving and affectionate.  

She is also great with young children and for the most part, knows not to jump or knock them over.  

She is crate-trained and potty-trained & would do best in a moderately active house.  

Since she is still learning her manners a bit, another doggy sibling who would play and tolerate her energy level would be ideal as well. 

 She has come such a long way in a very short time and we know that the perfect family is out there waiting for their “Lucky Penny”.

REQUIREMENTS:
-Must have fenced in yard

animal.description:
If you are interested in this dog, don't waste time with an inquiry! Fill out an application here to get the ball rolling...
https://pethavenmn.org/adopt/adoptable-dogs/dog-adoption-application/

Here is more about Speckles!

Nickname: Claude
3-year-old, 50-pound Lab mix

House-Trained: Yes
Crate-Trained: No – he has some separation anxiety and has broken out of two crates
Training: Food motivated and enjoys training sessions

Other Dogs: Not much on playing, but likes to sniff out and investigate 
Cats: Co-exists well with cats
Kids: Unknown, but due to his patient demeanor we think he would do fine

Claude is a loving, independent, outdoorsy lap dog. He adores attention and will get as close as possible to you and begin pawing to get some affection. 

Claude has enjoyed roaming around the backyard watching the neighbors and the snow fall. He is currently being treated for heart worm and so his activity is limited, but once treatment is complete and activity restrictions lifted, he would enjoy daily walks and time spent exploring the yard. We recommend a fenced yard as his exploring would take him into neighboring yards if given the chance. 

Claude is looking for a home with humans who are home more often than not and who do not mind giving lots of love and attention to this sweet boy!


His adoption fee includes spay/neuter, heartworm/Lyme test, all age-appropriate vaccinations (distemper, rabies, & Bordetella), HW and flea/tick preventative, and microchip implant and registration. 

There is no guarantee of age and breed as a rescue animal's history is unknown. All ages and breeds are best guess.

Adoption fees INCLUDE a mandatory sales tax of 7.525%.

Due to post-adoption services provided, it is Pet Haven's policy to only place dogs into homes within a 75-mile radius of the Minneapolis, MN city center.

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption questionnaire and e-mail it to adoptioncenter@homewardtrails.org.

Due to COVID-19 precautions, all animals for adoption through Homeward Trails can be met by appointment only. You can make an appointment to meet available dogs at our ADOPTION CENTER by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet and available cats at MEOW PALACE by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet1. 
For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time. 

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE: http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

Adoption Coordinator: Adoption Center
Location: Adoption Center

The adoption fee for this dog/puppy is $475. This fee includes spay/neuter and microchip. 

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

 We also provide free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program

animal.description: Staff would describe my personality as: Please read Zayda's bio closely. She's a very sweet and smart dog, but she'll need a specific type of home to be successful! Zayda is a very high energy dog. Zayda has not had proper guidance from humanst, so Zayda is prone to jumping on people and acting wildly and overly hyper when introduced to new people. Zayda is very easily stimulated, and sometimes she gets so stimulated that she just bursts with energy and has to run and run and run until she is calm again. When she cannot do that, such as when she is on leash, she will jump and nip and do anything she can to burn off the energy she's accumulated from the stimulation. Her previous family had to return her due to her inappropriate behavior. Zayda will need a family who has experience with very high energy dogs, and who understands how to properly train. She will need to live in a home with another high energy, friendly dog who can help her play appropriately and burn off her energy, and she will need an owner with the time to make meal time a mental exercise for her. Luckily this is very easy with all the different food puzzles on the market! Dog parks will NOT be an appropriate setting for her to burn off her energy, as that would likely be TOO much stimulation for her and have little opportunity to set appropriate guidelines for play. With other dogs I am: Great! I'd need a high-energy friend in the home to help me play. With cats I am: No good, I am too high energy for them. With children I am: Children may be in the picture for me later as I age and settle, but right now I need a home with no children as I am too hyper! Potty-trained: Yes Crate-trained: No Leash-trained: Yes Tricks: Sit, lay down I have the following special needs: I need a high-energy, dog-savvy home! Please read my bio above. All dogs are tested for heartworms and given flea preventatives. They are also tested for intestinal parasites and receive routine dewormings. Dogs are vaccinated against distemper, rabies, and bordetella, spayed/neutered before adoption, and have a microchip. Adoption fees include the initial automated registration of the microchip at the time of adoption.

animal.description: Meet Halley! Halley is an adorable 7 month old Beagle mix. Halley was brought up to Massachussetts from the south and still needs time to adjust to her new life. Once Halley has had the chance to get comfortable with you she is a total sweetheart! Due to Halley's fearfulness she is looking for an adult only home that is outside of the city, ideally in a more rural or suburban area. Having access to a fenced yard or easily accessible area for potty breaks would be helpful for housetraining due to her fearfulness, so we are looking to send her home to a fenced yard. Halley is looking for a quiet home with a family who can help her learn that new people and objects are not so scary. Halley has shown us that she heavily depends on other dogs to show her the ropes so she must live with at least one very friendly and social dog that will lead the way for her and help her adjust. When Halley is with other dogs she is much more confident, playful and vocal! We do not know how she would be with cats or other animals. Halley does not seem to know any cues and will need some training for basic commands in addition to working to show her that new people aren't so scary. Could this playful pup be a part of your family? This animal is currently up to date on all vaccinations, has been spayed, microchipped and been seen by our vet team. If you are interested in adopting this animal, please fill out our web form, available here: Dedham Adoption Inquiry Form! You can expect a response to your inquiry from a member of our adoption staff within 48 hours of completing this form. Due to our high volume of inquiries, please refrain from calling unless that time frame has passed. If needed, you can reach the Dedham shelter at 617-426-9170 x605. The Animal Rescue League of Boston is currently operating by appointment only Tuesday-Sunday 1pm-6pm. Our Adoption Forward process will start with a phone conversation. Also, be sure to check out our: * ARL Website * ARL Twitter * ARL Facebook * ARL Instagram

Due to Gracie's fearfulness she is looking for an adult only home that is outside of the city, ideally in a more rural or suburban area. We are looking to send her home to a fenced in back yard to run around in and have easy access for potty breaks. Gracie is looking for a relatively quiet home with a family who can help her learn that new people and objects are not so scary. At the shelter, Gracie has made many friends and is very playful. We feel that it would be very beneficial if she goes home to a confident, social dog. We do not know how she would be with cats or other animals. Gracie does not seem to know any cues and will need some positive reinforcement training for basic commands in addition to working to show her that new people aren't so scary. If you're looking for a loving, playful dog then Gracie might be the dog for you! This animal is currently up to date on all vaccinations, has been spayed, microchipped and been seen by our vet team. Her companion dog was a smaller female and we would recommend a slow introduction to another dog in the home, but we would really love to see Molly be the Queen of her castle!
Please note: We only accept adoption applications through our website or in person (Facebook and Petfinder inquiries are not considered applications).

animal.description:
Rocky / Male / 1 Year / 68lbs / Labrador Retriever Mix / Toronto

Meet Rocky! Rocky is described as sweet, curious, playful, intelligent, and active. He loves people and is happiest when receiving attention from his family and when he’s outside. He doesn’t have a huge interest in toys yet, but when he does decide to play, he likes to destroy a stuffy or chew on a Nylabone. He would do well in almost any environment outside of the city. He is more than ready for a loving and active family to call his own!

When walking down the street, Rocky shows interest in every person that passes him. He will want to greet some people and can get a little bouncy and eager to say hello. If someone has a bag, stroller or something unfamiliar on their person, he may be weary. Often, he will stop and stare at people getting out of their car or a garage door opening. He is very friendly but may need support and guidance on proper introductions. He doesn’t know his own size so may knock over small children during play. Regardless we predict he would love to share a home with respectful children!

Still very much a puppy, Rocky needs to be provided with appropriate places to chew. If he gets bored, he will often grab something he knows he’s not allowed to chew to get your attention. If he can’t be supervised, he will need to be put in a puppy proofed space with safe things to chew. He is a very good boy and can usually be redirected as needed. When left alone he may cry and few times but settles quickly. Rocky is fully potty trained and currently goes outside 4 times a day. Rocky is up at 7am and gets a one hour walk or run to start the day. He has 2 shorter potty breaks during the day, and his second long walk around 9:30pm. He enjoys his crate, and it is his safe space, he will sleep in it during the day and typically puts himself to bed after his late walk. He is still working on going into the crate on command.

Rocky is learning proper leash manners but will need continued support. He will pull when he sees/smells something and has selective hearing when he’s distracted. He has made huge progress with his leash skills in the 2 months that he has been in foster care and will even walk on a loose leash for extended periods of time. It’s clear he was not socialized properly with dogs and will bark, jump or growl when he sees them. He needs a strong and patient handler willing to work with him on this. Generally, he just wants to play with dogs but has never been taught how to approach. Rocky has been progressing very well in his reactivity to other dogs and if he is given enough space he will typically not react anymore. Rocky loves to chase squirrels and will need continued work on not learning to chase them while on leash.

Rocky’s ideal home would be a detached house, with a fully fenced backyard. He can not be trusted in an unsecured space yet and will need supervision even in the backyard as he is very athletic and can jump very high. He gets very distracted with the sounds of the city and is easily startled. He would thrive in the suburbs or quiet country. We predict he could live with another well-adjusted dog (he lived with them prior to coming to Canada) granted proper introductions are conducted. He will need an adopter with some dog experience and able to work through dog/squirrel reactivity. Rocky is only looking for cat free homes at this time.

Rocky is showing early stages of hip dysplasia. He will need to remain on glucosamine and chondroitin supplements throughout his life.

If you’re interested in adopting Rocky please apply at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/adoption-info#adoption-form

Rocky’s adoption fee is $800. To learn more about our adoption fees and the adoption process, please visit our FAQs at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/about-us#about-faqs

animal.description:
*** Available Wednesday 2/3 *** A Post-it left on the crate when Sweet Tea was found by Saving Grace had a single word on it- "SWEETIE." This became the inspiration for her foster-name because THAT'S what she turned out to be!

Though at first she was timid, very thin, and had a skin condition when she arrived, over the not-quite 5 weeks she's been with us in the foster program at SG she's blossomed into a 41 lb. healthy and happy pup. It's hard to tell exactly how old Sweet Tea is... She has all of her immaculately-white adult teeth. She had puppies; it was obvious she came to us right after weaning.

She can act like a puppy herself, though, and is amazing to watch She's long and, like a gazelle, bounds across the yard. Back to you, Sweet Tea runs up steps two and three at a time. She loves to go for walks and with her herding instinct needs a little guidance for how to "heel." A very enthusiastic and playful pup, Sweet Tea is also a "couch dog." She'll jump up next to you for lots of snuggles and back rubs, then warms the side of your leg as she circles up just like a puppy to fall asleep... sometimes for hours at a time.

Inquisitive enough to nibble on things, she listens and stops when told quietly to stop. Sweet Tea is housebroken and crate-trained for all her meals and snacks, and as long as she potties and has a dog bone treat when it's time to close up for the night, she willingly spends nights there too.

This girl is looking for her forever home one with someone calm to hang out with, maybe a fellow pup for fun, definitely a fence at least 4 feet high, and lots of love. If Sweet Tea sounds like your "cup of tea," please make an application for her at savinggracenc.org.

Please note we are working with limited staff/volunteers at this time. For full details of our current adoption appointment policy, please see https://savinggracenc.org/adoption-appointments-during-this-time/. Highlights:

We are working with a very limited staff/volunteer base

We do not have the people power to respond to emails/call about specific dogs

Our appointments are limited to 2 people at a time and for a maximum of 30 minutes.

Please arrive at your appointment ready to meet the dogs we have available. At this time, many dogs are in foster families or not yet posted on our website. Be flexible and ready to meet any number of wonderful dogs available onsite at the time of your appointment.

All puppies and dogs at Saving Grace are crate trained, have been spayed/neutered, are up to date on their vaccinations, are on heartworm preventative and have been microchipped. Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.

*** Available Wednesday 2/3 *** Scout has been a sweet, loving, playful, affectionate member of our family for the last two months while she finished nursing and weening her puppies. She quickly got to be part of our group of four dogs. She became good buddies w our hound dog Harper. The wrestled and spent time together everyday, and bounced and wagged their tails when it was time to play. While she was with us Scout got comfortable wearing a leash and harness and accompanied my family and one of our dogs on daily walks. She learned that being in a crate is a good thing and settles down quickly. At night she sleeps on her blanket on the floor of our our bedroom. Each night she collects two or three pairs of socks from the laundry and puts them on her blanket without damaging them. She buries her head in her pile of 'stolen' goods and falls asleep. Scout loves to play tug with a rope and chew on bully sticks. She is affectionate with my husband, daughter, and I and loves hugs, pats, and snuggles. Scout is getting used to the sounds and sights of living in a busy neighborhood. Sometimes she is a little hesitant on walks, but being with our other dog helps. She also responds well when we remind her what a good dog she is :). Scout is an all round amazing dog that will fit in well with loving humans. She would like to be around other dogs, either in your family or dogs that visit w friends. She is quite special and will bring a lot of joy to whoever adopts her.

Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Coming Soon!Papi is a 15 year old, 13 pound chihuahua mix. Sweet little senior boy, Papi, has had a challenging life. He lost his original owner nearly 12 years ago, and was recently rescued by animal control officers from a difficult hoarding situation. We don't know how he survived, but not only did he survive all of that, he did so all while living with a severely damaged eye. Thanks to his wonderful foster and specialty vets, we have learned so much about this sweet boy over the past few months.

Papi's damaged eye is not functional, but it is also not bothering him at all! According to Animal Eye Specialists, he is perfectly happy and healthy with the eye, so it can stay where it is. He will need follow up every six months or so just to be sure it remains stable.

Papi's foster family has learned that he is a happy, affectionate little boy who loves to take walks every day. He will even remind his foster mom if she is a little late starting his walk! Papi is fully housetrained, and is very good about letting his family know when he needs to go out. He loves to lay in the warm grass and watch birds. If left alone, he will dig, but quickly stops when told "No, Papi". He loves to sleep in his crate, and sleeps all night with no complaints. Because of his vision, Papi is cautious about going through doors and approaching new things, but he learns quickly with encouragement and love.

Papi is due for his neuter and chip in early February. He will be ready for his new , forever home soon after.

Prior to adoption, all dogs are spayed/neutered, tested for heartworm, vaccinated (including rabies, if age appropriate) and microchipped.

Adoption fees for dogs: http://www.svpetproject.org/info/adoption

Stay up-to-date on what our dogs are up to by following us on Facebook!

animal.description:
Gracie / Female / 4 Years / 56 lbs / American Bulldog Mix / Brampton

Meet Gracie! Gracie could be one of the sweetest dogs we’ve ever met. She loves everyone and just wants to be held and cuddled. She is never pushy and always respectful; she’s just happy to be close to her humans. She hasn’t shown much interest in toys yet, but she loves her rope toy! She is described as quiet, sweet, laid back, gentle, happy and affectionate. She is amazing with everyone, a true angel in dog form!

Gracie loves meeting new people - and will go right over and offer her head for pets. Recently she had a visit to the vet, and even though she was nervous she was still gentle and calm. She may let out a low growl at the mail person, but she is never aggressive. Gracie hasn’t been tested with children but we predict she would love them. Any kids in the home should be dog savvy and respect her space as needed.

Gracie is currently getting 2 walks a day plus additional opportunities to use the washroom. So far that has been enough exercise, but her fosters pay close attention to her energy levels in case she requires an additional walk. She is pretty lazy overall! Gracie has great house manners and never has accidents.

Gracie is crated while alone and settles right away. She never makes a sound and just sleeps until her humans let her out. On leash she pulls quite a bit and is very strong. She can only be walked by strong handlers and needs adopters comfortable with consistent redirection. She gets very excited when she sees squirrels and will try and take off after them. She is not fearful of anything, just over stimulated while outside.

Gracie doesn’t know many commands but is eager to make her people happy. She will sit on occasion and sometimes stay. She is food motivated so would love to learn more!

Gracie’s ideal home would be a house with a backyard, with lots of space to explore outside. She would prefer to be outside of the city. Gracie could potentially adapt to an apartment, granted her exercise needs are met. She loves to explore the outdoors so she would do best with a family that enjoys walking and hiking. Gracie has not be tested with other animals, but does not seem bothered by other dogs. Due to her prey drive, she is looking for a cat-free home. Gracie would prefer a family who is home more often than not and has lots of time to spend with her!

If you’re interested in adopting Gracie please apply at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/adoption-info#adoption-form

Gracie’s adoption fee is $800. To learn more about our adoption fees and the adoption process, please visit our FAQs at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/about-us#about-faqs.

animal.description:
IF YOU CAN SEE THIS POSTING, THIS ANIMAL IS STILL HAVING APPLICATIONS BEING TAKEN ON THEM. WE UPDATE OUR SITE DAILY.

Meet Mila!

She's a 4yo boxer/lab mix who is a total sweetheart! One of her ears is typical boxer & the other ear is more lab LOL. This poor girl has had her share of pups over the years it seems and now she's ready to be a dog and not just a Mom. She is up to date on her vaccines, has been spayed & is HW neg. We're pretty sure she lived with dogs in her past life but doesn't really interact with those in her fosterhome. We have no idea about cats but boxers typically have a fairly high prey drive, so we're not recommending that she be put into a home with one. The shelter said she's ok with kids but we have no way of confirming that here so we would not be comfortable with her going to a home with young children. It took her some time to trust but now loves to snuggle with us! 10 days into her stay here she picked up a bone to chew for the very first time so we're not quite sure if she's just more comfortable or simply doesn't know much about toys. If your schedule has her alone for multiple hrs during a typical day, please don't apply as she simply loves people too much for that. Mila's fully housetrained & is fairly good on a leash too! She's got it all

If you think you may be a match please submit an app from our site at endingthesadness.org to be considered. Our driving radius for adopters is 2hrs.

animal.description:
Jet is one very special guy looking for someone to share his heart with. He arrived he was feeling very overwhelmed and nervous, but he is settling in, starting to feel more confident and secure in this big place. Jet is hoping for a kind, calm owner and a home that is steady and predictable so he can relax and enjoy life. He will rely on the bond you build to guide him in the outside world and will need to trust in you not to put him in situations that he can not handle by himself. If people rush in and don't spend time letting him feel comfortable and get to know you, it worries him so he will need slow introductions and patient people. If you go slow and steady he opens up and will trust you. Jet likes playing with other dogs, but can also get worried with new dogs so he is looking for a polite, well socialized dog he can play with. Jet is hoping for a calm gentle person and a calm steady home filled with love!

If you are interested in learning more about Jet, please email the behavioral team at kheadlee@wenatcheehumane.org with some information on your current living situation and a phone number.

animal.description:
Daisy has been in and out foster for the last few months recovering from FHO surgery on her hind leg, but is ready to find her forever home! She has healed excellently, and her current foster says she is a super easy going girl who loves walks, is housetrained, and likes playing with her cat!

A note from her current foster says:

"On walks Daisy is not spooked by cars or trucks and is VERY happy to go on walks! She is curious about people, dogs, and squirrels, but does a great job of not interacting or chasing . Daisy walks very well overall. She stops when I stop, and responds quickly to her name.

In the house Daisy is definitely house trained. She did not whine or bark in her crate overnight, and wants to play with my cat!! Daisy is super patient and gentle (my cat is still getting used to her), when let outside to our fenced in backyard she goes to the bathroom almost immediately and comes right back to the door. She seems to just want to be around me and hangout. Has been super cuddly, but also playful when I want to play

Daisy is incredibly sweet and would make a great fit for someone looking for a companion or a great family dog. "
Do you think I am the perfect match for you? Click on the link below for the Meet Your Match questionnaire. We will forward your information to the foster parent for follow up. This information will be used to make sure this is a good fit before we schedule a meet and greet.
Let's get started on meeting me! https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSeOSn7D67PzZ98rWlpCkNUL9aaxFLVAk7m1ucMF3fFj7JWzgQ/viewform?usp=sf_link

animal.description:
Humane Society/SPCA of Nelson County - ALMOST HOME

29 Stagebridge Road, Lovingston, VA 22949

Phone: 434 263-7722
Email: pets@nelsonspca.org

IMPORTANT!!! PLEASE READ

Posted animals are physically located at the above address except when indicated with the following notations after the animal's name:

Animal Name (FC=initials) -- indicates the animal is living in Foster Care. To meet the animal, please contact the foster directly when contact information is provided; otherwise call the shelter at 434 263-7722.

Animal Name (COURTESY) - this animal is posted as a public courtesy using information provided by the owner. Our shelter does not own or guarantee the information provided by the owner to be complete and accurate. Also, adoption does not involve our shelter but is strictly between the adopter and the owner.

18 POUNDS OF BEAGLE ADORABLENESS!!!UPDATE 1/30/21.
Eighteen pounds of beagle adorableness is easy to love. With velveteen ears, soulful eyes, black and tan fur beautifully balanced, Earl could challenge any movie star dog for cuteness.
Estimated to be 2-3 years old, he is a quiet little guy at Almost Home. Though he is slightly wary, this small gentleman enjoys calm attention, food puzzle toys, and special treats.
He was friendly toward us from the beginning, yet if we tried to leash him, or if he thought we were out to grab him, he would shy away from us. His eyes told us, he interpreted this as capture. With patient convincing, it did not take long for him to understand that a leash isn't a bad thing, and that being petted was kind of nice. His little heart is coming to believe that no one is out to get him, and his trust and confidence builds daily.
Poor Earl was left abandoned and infected with heart worms before Animal Control picked him up for his own safety. No one came to say he was theirs and take him home. Now that he is with us, we are making sure he can have a healthy happy life. Earl will begin Heart-worm treatment in April.
Earl would do best in a calm household with patient folks who want to share their home with a gentle dog who needs tender care.
Are you the person who can give this worthy little dog a chance to have the good life he deserves?

NOTE: All animals are spayed/neutered as soon as practical after arriving at our facility unless there is a medical issue that may cause a delay or they are too young to be spayed/neutered.VOLUNTEERS and DONATIONS NEEDED. Visit our website for more info: http://nelsonspca.org

animal.description:
Errol is the sweetest dog with the best personality. He loves all people and is good with other dogs especially if they will play with him. He cannot run too far but enjoys a good wrestle. He lays quietly on his dog bed while his foster mom works from home. He is crate and house trained. He is super food motivated. He weighs about 60lbs and should not gain any more weight for easy of movement.

Now to the story of how he came to be with us and missing his leg. He was found wondering in neighborhood. He had been there about a week with his leg dragging and trying to find food and shelter. Finally someone offered him some help and got him to us. We got his leg amputated as it was a Brachial Plexus Avulsion.

If you are interested in adopting Errol please submit an inquiry directly with Greater Charlotte SPCA by visiting charlottespca.org/adopt.

animal.description: Say hello to Sherlock! Sherlock is a two-year-old St Bernard / Great Pyrenees Mix who is a bundle of energy! He is a sweet boy who get along with anyone he meets and loves to play with dogs. He is big, 125 pounds and doesn't realize his size, so he would be best in a family without small children. He is very energetic and agile. He must go to a family with a huge yard (1+acres) to allow him to run and play and it must be fenced with a 6' high fence. He easily jumps the 4' fence at his foster home without touching it. He would love to go to a family with another big dog (but no cats) so they can play. Sherlock is a dominant male, so a home with a female or a laid back male is best. Sherlock has had very limited training, so his new owner would need to be willing and able to work with him on his manners. He currently knows how to sit and down and is working on walking on a leash without pulling. Sherlock is house trained and can be trained to sleep in an extra-large crate. If you are ready to welcome this giant goof-ball into your home and interested in learning more about Sherlock, put in an application at eapl.com. His adoption fee is $250

Hi I am Mr. Zucchini. I am a very small and sweet guy. I was abandoned at animal control because my original family was moving and didn't want to take me with them. I like to sleep in the bed with my people, am housebroken, ride good in the car, and just love to be around people. Our adoption fees are:
Dogs: $155
Cats: $95
Puppies under 4 months: $115 plus S/N Deposit: $100
Kittens under 4 months: $70 plus S/N Deposit: $100

All pets available for adoption have been spayed or neutered (unless under 4 months please read about our adoptions
here
), are current on vaccinations and preventatives, and micro-chipped. Cats have been tested and confirmed negative for Feline AIDS and Leukemia. Dogs have been tested for heartworm disease.

Our shelter is located at 42 Deep River Rd in Sanford and is open Tues, Thurs, & Fri from 3pm - 7pm & Sat from 10-2pm (other times available by appointment). CARA's adoption process and online application can be found at
http://www.cara-nc.org/info/adoption

Please call 919-774-9433, email adoptions@cara-nc.org, or visit www.cara-nc.org for information about this or other pets available for adoption.

If you would like to adopt me or any of my friends, please visit CARA to fill out an on-line application or e-mail us at adoptions@cara-nc.org.

Every animal that comes into the CARA program is here because one or more events occurred that led to this animal needing not only a home, but a person or family to love and protect them. Each animal has been loved and cared for by a small and determined group of people who want nothing more than to know each animal is safe for the rest of his or her life. Thank you for looking to adopt!

animal.description:
Very shy - patient home needed!Meet Tank!

He is 4.5 years old and weighs about 11#. Mr. Tank came into our rescue as an owner surrender, and came to us VERY skittish and fearful. He has been in his current foster home for about 2 months, and through patience and kindness, Tank is finally starting to open up! He was not accepting of any kind of affection for about 2 weeks (meaning his foster mom was not even able to touch him), and the foster mom has slowly been introducing affection at Tank's pace, and we are finally seeing him enjoying his affection (this happened about weeks 6 to 8).

He is pee pad trained, and when he first goes to his new adoptive home, he is going to need to be given a pen with pee pads available, and given lots of time to decompress without a lot of pressure put on him.

He does co-exist with the other dogs in the house very well, and actually seems to draw a lot of confidence by following the other dogs. For this reason, we would LOVE to see him go to a home with another dog to help continue to build his confidence.

His perfect home will be a quiet and patient home, one that will go slow with him and let him open up at his pace. We are not recommending children because of his level of insecurity/fear.

He is going to take a couple months until he is fully comfortable and comes out of his shell.

He is up to date on all shots, dewormed, and neutered. He has been heartworm tested (negative) and is on prevention. The adoption fee is $250.00 If you are interested in adopting this pet please fill out an application.

http://www.ajssearchandrescue.org/adoption-application

Puppies that are under 4 months old cannot be adopted outside of our Veterinary Service area. Please call for specific locations. Children under 8 years old often are not a good match for our puppies and dogs. In order to protect both, your child and our rescued dogs/puppies from harm, we seldom if ever adopt to families with young children.
Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet at one of our adoption events. Thank you for considering a rescue! The adoption fee includes vaccinations, Bordetella, de-worming, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip. There is a an additional $12.99 fee for Home Again for a lifetime registration of the microchip.
Puppies cannot be adopted outside of the Houston area until they are spay/neutered after they are 4 months old. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.
NOTE: In our bios, we provide information based on our volunteer's experience with a particular dog; such as temperament, training, and ability to get along with others.
AARF is a 501(c)3 Non Profit, all breed, no kill organization. Our group is always in need of donations in order to continue to give the needed medical care to our rescues. Adoption fees do not begin to cover all of the medical costs. Any donation , no matter how small is a big help and is greatly appreciated. Please help us to continue to help them. Thank you.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Elliot! I was rescued by a shelter in Georgia before arriving at the Big Dog Ranch Rescue. I'm not a puppy anymore, but I'm only 2 years old, and still very much like a big baby! I am extremely loveable and enormously playful. I would probably be a great family pet, but would do better around older children, as my energy level might be a little bit much for little ones. I would love to find a home that has a great big yard for me to run around in and get out some of my energy. I'd love a busy home with lots of things that I can be a part of, particularly one that receives lots of visitors who I can engage with. I may be the type of pup that you can bring out and about with you in public after some time and some training. I could definitely benefit from continued obedience training, as well as potty-training, but I have learned to walk well on a leash and I just can't wait to get a chance to do that with you very soon!

Name: Marley
Weight: approx 65-70lbs
Age: 1 year
Gender: Female
Spayed/Neutered: yes
Breed: German Shepherd/mastiff mix
Color: tan

Good with adults: yes

Good with kids: not really but only been around them a handful of times; Just too big and energetic

Good with other dogs: yes, goes to daycare and is very attached to one of my others.

Good with cats: I’m not sure never been around them.

House trained: yes

Crate trained: yes but still barks when she hears something.

Energy level: high puppy

Can be handled/touched: yes

Barker: when in a kennel or outside and see/hear something someone.

Flight risk: to run away? I would say possibly. She’s run off before but came back 30 mins later ?????

Food aggressive: sometimes growls if another dog comes by her

Walks on leash: yes but needs more work.

Rides well in car: needs to be tethered; she’s all over and wants to hang out the window.

Destructive: still a big puppy; mostly has a favorite type of organic bone I found that she is attached too. If she has that she’s fine. (Can pass the info on that along to whomever takes her in)

Needs a home with a yard: YES

Needs a home with another dog: I’m not really sure. I’m sure she would enjoy it. I have two others but they’re older. She likes to play.

Can live in an apartment: I would say no due to her energy level

Backstory: someone reached out to me on Facebook about Marley. Her owner is newly pregnant and feels three dogs are going to be tough to manage once the baby arrives. Marley is already spayed and has been well cared for.
