animal.description: Hello! I am new to the shelter! Please keep checking my profile for updates as the staff gets to know me better! I was surrendered to the shelter with my brother Elvis because our owners fell ill and could no longer care for us. We refuse to go anywhere without each other! Which means we need to go to our forever home together. Don't let our ages fool you we still have a lot of spunk! We enjoy the company of just about everybody we meet. We have done well with children in our previous home. We are unsure about cats but can be cat tested here at the shelter. If you are intersted in us call our friends at the shelter for more information! If this dog has been successful in our play groups it is not a guarantee that a dog will be social with other dogs in their home or in public settings. Dogs are individuals and have personality conflicts, just like us. Play groups do not guarantee that territorial or resource guarding issues will not surface in the home. While play groups do help us get to know the dog's better, once they are adopted their new environments and new relationships will influence their behavior in ways we cannot predict. The Adoption Fee Includes: - initial canine distemper combination vaccination - first worming or stool check - rabies vaccination (for animals over 3 months of age) - AVID microchipping - flea treatment/preventative - spaying or neutering Adoption fee: $87.50 Per state law, ALL ADOPTERS must purchase a non-refundable 2021 dog license at time of adoption for any canine three months and older. The cost of the license is $7.00. (Senior Citizen or Person with Disability-$5.00) Leash and collar included.

animal.description:
LOVING THE GOOD LIFE:  5 – 6 months old / Currently 33 lbs. 

Hi, my name is Julia!  I’m a young pup who somehow ended up at animal control.  I am looking forward to finding my furever family in a loving home.

• OTHER DOGS/CATS/KIDS:  There are 3 silly and rambunctious dogs in my foster home, and I do very well with them. I’d really like to have another dog in my new home as I follow their lead and it gives me confidence, so let’s meet (It may just take a day or so to feel comfortable with them) / I get along well with the cat in my foster home.  I’m curious but not aggressive with her, so if you have a cat that likes dogs, let’s meet / I enjoyed the company of the gentle 9-year-old in my 1st short break foster home as well as the kids I met at MM’s that were around that age as well.  We did lots of snuggling, so if you have kids, let’s meet but best no toddlers that I may bump over.

• PERSONALITY/ENERGY LEVEL:  I was shy the first day in my foster home, but they spent a little time with me on the floor and that really helped me warm up and feel comfortable with them.  Now I’m just the sweetest dog with a super soft coat to boot.  I was also shy and timid in my early days at Mostly Mutts - being young and a bit confused from being at animal control, I needed to adjust and feel safe.  I’m quiet in my foster home and they have only heard me bark once – my foster was giving out treats and I sang for joy about that!   I am friendly and give tail wags now as I’m enjoying life with a great foster family / My energy level right now is 3-5, but I think it will increase as I get more comfortable and even more of my personality emerges.

• SKILLS/CRATE/POTTY:  I’m a pretty smart puppy and so far, I’ve learned the ‘sit’, ‘stay’, and ‘come’ commands.  I also greet nice strangers without jumping and my leash manners are pretty good too.  I do sometimes hesitate at doorways but go through them with encouragement / My crate manners were good at Mostly Mutts.  In my foster home, I have good house manners and do not need a crate / After one initial accident, my potty habits have been good in my foster home.  I follow the other dogs and go to the door when I need to go out.  It takes me a few minutes to go potty when I am on my leash, so patience, please.

• LIKES/DISLIKES:  I like to show my family I love them by giving them kisses.  I also love to play tug-o-war and play with plush toys.  Being outside with my people and the other dogs in the home is fun, so let’s spend time together enjoying the great outdoors.  I like to find familiar places to settle down in / I didn’t seem to like the TV in my 1st short break foster home, as it seemed new and confusing to me, but I’m sure I’ll get used to it.   I would not be happy if I didn’t get the love, training and good care that all dogs deserve.

• MEDICAL:   I'm current on vaccinations, micro-chipped and spayed.

I am looking for a wonderful family to give me a loving home!  My adoption fee is $299.00, and I’m located in Kennesaw, Ga.
animal.name: Julia

animal.description: New year, new diet, amiright? Let's be honest, who doesn't need to work off some pandemic pounds? And in addition to exercise, a healthy diet is a must, including plenty of quinoa. Meet Quinoa. This handsome tricolor guy came to PACC as a stray with a buddy who has since been adopted, but now that he's flying solo, he's winning hearts all over the shelter. In play group, Quinoa greeted other dogs appropriately, despite being a little bit nervous due to some lameness in one of his legs. Volunteers say he's a calm-tempered gentleman who wants pets and to be loved. The shelter can be a noisy place for a dog that may be feeling vulnerable or challenged, so Quinoa would love to get into a home of his very home. Quinoa can be a bit picky when it comes to treats, but he especially loves cheese. He's a friendly and affectionate guy who seeks out love and pets and back rubs. After being on his own for so long, Quinoa is very underweight and would love to find himself a person or people who can shower him with affection and help to fatten him up. Quinoa is a total sweetheart who would make for a wonderful sidekick. If this gentle boy sounds like the pup for you, make an appointment to meet him today.

animal.description:
‘DISNEY PRINCESS’ THEMED PUPPY:  6 – 7 months old / Currently 20 lbs.

Hi there!  My name’s Jasmine!  I was at animal control with my sisters, and together we’re the Disney Princess puppies.  Mostly Mutts rescued us, and now we’re all excited to meet our new families soon and start living ‘happily ever after’ in a loving home!  

• OTHER DOGS/CATS/KIDS:  I love my siblings and got along great and played well with the other big dogs in my short break foster home.  So, I would likely enjoy another dog to play with in my new home.  If you have a nice doggie that would like a puppy friend, let’s meet / I haven’t met kitties yet, so let’s meet / There were two boys in my short break foster home (ages 5 and 8), and I did great with them – from cuddling to playing, so I’d likely enjoy kids (around that age or older) in my new home, as long as they are gentle with me and best no toddlers that may fall on me.  Let’s meet!

• PERSONALITY/ENERGY LEVEL:  I am a wonderful young girl – active, playful, friendly, and curious.  I view myself as a lap dog and really enjoyed my foster mom’s lap for the week I spent with them – lol. I was pretty quiet with minimal barking in my foster home and my foster reported that I had pretty good manners for a young pup, so yay me / My energy level is 6-8, so plan on being active with me, so I get the exercise I need to be a happy pup and adult dog.

• SKILLS/CRATE/POTTY:  I’m now in the Mostly Mutts University training program and looking forward to learning lots of new things!  I’ll also want my family to continue my training, so I know everything I need to know to grow up and become a wonderful adult dog, so get ready for some training with your new best friend / I slept through the night in a crate in my foster home and did well in it, though it took a little coercing – like a treat to get me to go into it.  My crate manners are good at Mostly Mutts too/ My potty habits have been pretty good.  I had a couple accidents before learning the schedule in my foster home.  I understand the concept of going potty outside and just need practice with letting my people know when I need to go out.  I don’t like to go potty outside in bad weather (but what doggie does).  I WILL do it but want to come right back inside.  So, be consistent with my training and I should have it down soon. 

• LIKES/DISLIKES:  I liked chasing tennis balls and sticks in the yard of my foster home, so a fenced yard where we can play would be nice in my new home.  As much as I like outdoor play, I prefer hanging out inside.  I love to cuddle in my people’s lap, and I am a big fan of my food / I can’t think of things I don’t like yet since I’m so young, but I’m sure I wouldn’t like it if I didn’t get enough love, attention, exercise and training.

• MEDICAL:  I'm current on vaccinations, micro-chipped and spayed.                                    

I am looking for a family dedicated to continuing my training, so I can be my best adult doggie self!  My adoption fee is $299.00, and I’m located in Kennesaw, Ga.

animal.description:
Meet Matt (Dillon)
This handsome pup is called Matt Dillon. Besides his obvious good looks, Matt is a happy and fun pup. We rescued Matt from a high-kill shelter. Since arriving he’s been a ball. 
Matt is about eight months old. He’s thought to be a Rhodesian Ridgeback/Chesapeake Bay Retriever. He has a beautiful chestnut colored coat and weighs 38 lbs., but he will grow a bit more. Matt loves being with people and is affectionate and friendly. Matt has a lot of energy and loves running and playing in the yard. He seems to be dog friendly, but will give chase to cats and would be best in a home without them. Matt is learning how to walk on a leash. He will do great with some gentle training. Matt will also do best in an active house, where he gets to be part of the activities and has a way to expend his energy.  
Matt is going to make for a super family companion. If you’re looking for a happy and outgoing, young dog to welcome to your heart and home, Matt may be the one. We all fell in love with him the minute he arrived and think you will too!
If interested in Matt, please submit an application online at: https://www.charlessmithgallhumanesociety.org/page/dog-adoption-application 
Once an application is submitted online, you will receive an email saying your application has been successfully submitted.  If you don’t receive this email within 24 hours, please check to make sure all application fields were completed or please call our shelter at 706-865-4135. All adopters must complete an approval process which involves a reference check with current/recent vet and a brief home visit if located in the immediate area. We do permit out of state adoptions. Adopters MUST come to the shelter to transport their new family member home. We do not ship nor do we transport them to their new homes. Adoption policies and application procedures are detailed at the shelter website: http://smithgallhumanesociety.org/ under tab All Adoptable Animals.
Charles Smithgall Humane Society (CSHS) is a No kill shelter. Animals in our care remain safe with us until adopted. Resident animals are primarily owner relinquished and also accepted from local Animal Control. The facility usually is operating at capacity with a list of animals waiting for space to open.
Adoptions and meet and greets are being scheduled by appointment only. Please call our office, email us or complete an application and someone will be in touch just as soon as they can. 
Location: 4823 Helen Hwy., Sautee, GA 30571, Phone: 706-865-4135
Email: smithgallhumanesociety@windstream.net
Our shelter in Sautee GA is located about 3 miles south of the alpine town of Helen in northeast GA.

animal.description:
‘DISNEY PRINCESS’ THEMED PUPPY:  6 – 7 months old / Approximately 14 lbs.

Hi there!  My name’s Aurora!  I was at animal control with my sisters, and together we’re the Disney themed puppies.  Mostly Mutts rescued us, and now we’re all excited to meet our new families soon and start living ‘happily ever after’ in a loving home!  

• OTHER DOGS/CATS/KIDS:  I love my siblings and would likely enjoy another dog to play with in my new home as I seem to want to play with the ones I see on my walks.  I am however afraid of the big dog that lives in the neighborhood who barks at me, so let’s meet / I haven’t met kitties yet, so let’s meet / I like the 12-year-old in my foster home but am a little mouthy, so best no toddlers that I may play a little too rough with, and of course let’s meet!

• PERSONALITY/ENERGY LEVEL:   I’m described as playful, cuddly, friendly, and very energetic!  I am the runt of my littermates, but I don’t let that get me down as I have a fun and sweet spirit / I have a higher energy level at about 6-8, so I’ll want regular exercise with my family! 

• SKILLS/CRATE/POTTY:  I’m looking for a family that will teach me everything I need to know to grow up and become a wonderful adult dog!  I’m working on ‘sit’ in my foster home / Right now I do not like the crate at all – barking when in it, etc.  Hopefully, you can show me that it’s not a bad place by giving me treats or a nice bone to chew when in it, etc.  Since I’m loud in my crate, an Apartment/Condo type home is likely not a good fit / I’m doing pretty well with my potty training when on a good schedule, but I have had accidents in my foster home, so you will need to finish my potty training. 

• LIKES/DISLIKES:  I like so many things, here is a little list for you:  toys including the stuffed kind, playing, being active with my family, napping, going for walks and socks – sorry about that last one (lol).  I also love food and will likely do some good growing now that I am getting regular meals.  You see I came to MM’s rather malnourished and weighted much less than my siblings / I’m not a fan of bursts of air – maybe I just don’t know why they happen, so it scares me.  Also, big dogs barking at me makes me want to get away from them.  Other than that, I would not be happy if I didn’t get enough love, attention, training and exercise.  

• MEDICAL:  I'm current on my vaccinations, micro-chipped and spayed.  Since I was malnourished, I came to MM’s walking more on my wrists, but I’ve made a remarkable recovery with just the good nutrition my little body needed!  As I get older, you may want to start me on glucosamine a little early.   

I’m looking for a family that will treasure me and give me a wonderful home, so if you’re ready to raise a great dog, I could be the one for you!  My adoption fee is $299.00, and I’m located in Kennesaw, Ga.

animal.description:
Hello there! I think I just received the letter you sent me. It went like this:
Dear Abby,
Will you love me forever and ever if I adopt you?
Sincerely,
Your Future Mom/Dad  
I have an answer for you! I sure will love you to pieces forever and ever if you will love me forever and ever too?!  
My name is Dear Abby, but I let all my dear friends call me Abby. I am an 8 years young, 57lb. black lab mix darling. I am a smart girl who is house trained, crate trained, good on a leash, and I even know how to "sit" and "come" when you ask me nicely! I adore humans of all ages and get along with cats. I do not enjoy sharing my loves with other canines, so I want to be your only dog. I am so fabulous you won’t even want another dog!  I mean look at this face: I melt hearts for a living with it!  I would be so happy lounging with you in our house, apartment, or even the cab of your big rig! I am definitely a lady who loves to lounge, but I also have adorable spurts of playful energy! I have a slight limp in my left leg from some old nerve damage, but it doesn't slow me down a bit! I just say that, like any good model, I have a signature walk. I am a sweet, loving, fun, happy girl who is wagging up a storm thinking of our life together! I will be your dearest friend for life if you fill out my adoption application and promise to love me for all of it!


My adoption fee is $75 and includes my spay/neuter, vaccinations, wellness exam, heartworm test, and microchip! If you're interested in meeting/adopting me, please visit www.rescueonespringfield.com/our-adoption-process/adoption-application/ and fill out the form! We do adopt out of state with vet references and video home check. *Adopter is responsible for coming to get the dog and returning the dog if the adoption does not work out* 

Don't forget to LIKE us on Facebook!-www.facebook.com/rescueonespringfield

*Remember, dogs are pack animals. Because of this, Rescue One does not adopt to outdoor-only homes. Pets are family and are not disposable.  Please make sure that you are 100% committed to a pet before considering adding one to your home.

animal.description:
Meet Sophie! She was surrendered yesterday when her owners could no longer handle her and her litter mate, who kept fighting. Sophie is 4 years old, about 65 lbs and amazing with people but must be the only pet in the home. No other dogs, no cats. Kids are a maybe - depending on the kids.

=====
FOLLOW THESE INSTRUCTIONS TO BE CONSIDERED: 

To adopt, complete the application at tarnj.org/adopt

If you have any questions at all, please DO NOT use the PetFinder inquiry form as we do not respond to those. Questions should be sent to info@tarnj.org. 

An application is required before any meets are scheduled so the best way to be considered is to apply ASAP at tarnj.org/adopt.

We are all volunteer-run and do our best to respond to every application. If there is a match with your application, you should hear from us within 2-5 days. If you do not hear from us, please check your Junk folder or email us for an update.

animal.description:
Freddy ACCT-A-83354

Intake: Stray. APO Pick up
Age: 5Y
Sex: Male
Altered: No

Medical Observation: 1/28 (Intake Exam)-- ABRASION ON NECK

Behavior Observation:
1/30 (Per Staff)-- Kennel Presentation--Easy to leash/social--Barking in kennel, but stopped and approached handler when kennel was opened. Easy to leash and lead out. Returned with a treat to coax into kennel and did not feel comfortable getting leash. An ACA assisted later and Freddy was hard barking in kennel and showing teeth.
Leash Skills--Pulls Minimally On Leash--Walked well on leash
Handleability---Tense/Allows some handling---Tense body, but allowed handling and petting when first in office. Immediately wen for toys when in the office. Handler held up a tennis ball to get attention for a picture and Freddy started hard barking and showing teeth. Freddy continued to do so with various toys in the office.
Tag--Did not attempt
Toys--Aggressive--Will accept trades, but shows teeth and will hard back if you present him with a toy.
 1/28 (Per Vet) BAR;FRIENDLY
1/27 (Per Finder)-- he got along with the children inside and was nice and laid back.

animal.description:
I have an Adoption Pending and will be going home soon.  But I hope you will consider one of our other wonderful dogs in need.  Thank you!

Sydney is a sweet 9-10 month old retrieve mix who found her way to our rescue through a shelter in Mobile County, AL. The story goes that someone called the shelter and said they found this puppy and asked that the animal control officer come and pick her up.  Was Sydney a stray or was she this family's dog?  Some folks say they found a dog when they no longer want them or cannot find homes for puppies because owner turn-ins are the first to be euthanized.  Strays at least have a 5-10 day hold, which gives time for a rescue to step in and rescue the dog.  And we at SGRR were more than happy to say YES to rescuing Sydney!

Sydney will certainly turn heads when you are out and about with her.  She has a beautiful white coat with a few golden patches.  She walks fairly well on a harness but does pull a bit when on a slip lead.  We imagine recreational walks were not part of Sydney's former life.  She is somewhat reserved when first meeting new people and in new situations.  She would do best in a calm home without a lot of comings and goings.  Sydney enjoyed playing with one of the vet tech's 3-year old daughter who is gentle and dog-savvy, but a home with active children would not suit Sydney well.

Sydney weighs about 50 lbs.  She has been brought up-to-date on vaccinations, was spayed, is heartworm negative, and has been micro-chipped.   She will be ready to come north in mid-February to be directly adopted - right in time to be someone's Valentine!!  A physically fenced yard is preferred for Sydney.  We know she will be an amazing pet - it will simply take her some time to get used to new things.  

Rescued dogs come with a range of needs - from behavioral to emotional to medical.  When approved applicants adopt such dogs, they agree to continue the rehabilitation we have begun.        

If not yet approved for adoption, please visit our website to learn more and to submit an online application:     http://sunshinegoldenrescue.com/adoption-info1.html  

Please DO NOT use the ASK ABOUT button to contact us, about this dog, as that will delay our ability to respond to your inquiry.  Please direct any questions regarding your application status to:  ajpillinger@gmail.com   

Thank you!
 
ABOUT OUR RESCUE
Before being approved to adopt, all potential adopters will be required to complete our online application and participate in our pre-adoption review process. The process includes the completion of an online application, a reference from the applicants' vet, a phone interview, and a visit to the applicants' home.  The application process helps us determine what type of Golden would be best suited for the applicants' life style.  In some cases, the specific dog you are interested in may have found a home before this process is complete or further assessment may indicate that this dog is not the right match for your family.  We are frequently getting new Goldens in need of a home, so we encourage you to apply and complete the application process so that when the right dog comes along you will be ready. 

The information provided on each dog is based on the observations of our vets, volunteers, fosters, and when available, trainers. While we do our best to report any and all issues, SGRR does not make any guarantees as to the health or temperament of any dog. Dogs evolve differently in different environments and we cannot predict with any certainty how the dog you adopt will behave and adapt in your home.

SGRR ADOPTION FEES - Effective May 1, 2020  (subject to change)
  
  $750    Puppy - up to 6 months              
  $650    Young 6 months - 6 years            
  $550    Senior 7 - 9  years                       
  $450    Senior 10 years and older          
 
  $550    Young Special Needs                
  $400    Senior 7+ Special Needs                

$1000    Young Bonded Pair                   
  $900    Senior 7+ Bonded Pair         

A contract is signed on the day of adoption.  Under the terms of the contract, all adopters are required to bring their SGRR dog to a vet within 7 business days.  All dogs receive basic veterinary care prior to adoption.  However, if an adopter's vet identifies an illness that an adopter is not willing to treat, then the dog may be returned and a full refund would be provided. 

Most of our dogs are fostered in private homes.  We do not have a facility to visit.  We are committed to our dogs before, during, and after adoption! To this end, the rescue retains an interest in each dog and our dogs can never be surrendered, re-homed, or sold. Should an adopter no longer be able to keep their SGRR dog, SGRR must be notified so that we can take the dog back into rescue and place it into another home. We reserve the right to remove a dog at any time should we find the adopter is no longer providing proper care.  Adopters agree to follow up visits as needed.  

Please be a ray of light for this Sunshine dog and make a tax deductible donation toward medical care and other expenses.   Every cent of your generosity goes directly toward the care of a Sunshine dog.

Please visit our website at: http://sunshinegoldenrescue.com  to learn more about our rescue and to make a Donation to support Sunshine Golden Retriever Rescue.  

THANK YOU!

animal.description:
Meet Po!

Hello there, my name is Po. I'm about 8 years old and about 67 pounds. I'm a real good boy and get along with with all my foster fur siblings, cats and dogs alike. Although I don't like sharing my toys all too much, I take correction from my humans well when it comes right down to it. I also take cues from other dogs if they don't want me to be in their space. I could live with older, respectful kids, but because I don't like my feet touched, little kids might not understand not to touch them. I'm completely housetrained and will hold it until I'm let outside, and will even let you know when I need to go. I don't need to be put in a crate when you aren't home, because although I'm not fond of being left alone, I'm still not destructive as long as I can't get to the garbage. I love eating, so the garbage just calls me right over to it when my humans aren't home and tempts me to get into it. Who knew the garbage could talk, right? But that's an easy enough fix I would think. 

Foster mom says I'm the perfect combination of playful and lazy. I love to play fetch with a ball, toy, or stick, and will happily bring it back to you for another toss. I really enjoy stuffies too! I walk well on a leash and would enjoy going on walks with you. I'm also a good boy on car rides. You wanna snuggle on the couch during rainy days? I'm good at that too! At the end of the day I'd love to sleep in bed with you if it's not too crowded, otherwise I'll find a comfy spot on the floor. Do you have a spot in your heart and home for a guy like me? 

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

WI Dept. Of Agriculture License Number: 474085-DS

Drop the confetti, pop the champagne, I am ready to celebrate! 

What are we celebrating? You falling head over heals for me of course! 

Hi, I am Confetti! I am a cute, meatbally pitty mix, and 7 years old. I came to the shelter with my friend Champagne after a housefire had left us homeless. The staff describe me as a doll. I know, its one of the perks of adopting a senior. I like going on walks and enjoy rolling in the grass when the snow is melted. I am not a snow girl at all. I love the warmth so be prepared to share you blankies, bed, and lap with me. If you would like to take me home, please fill out an application, call the shelter people to state interest and/or schedule an appointment to meet me! I promise you wont be disappointed!

animal.description: Let us introduce you to Janey, also known as Lilbit! She is a beautiful little girl full of life and love. She LOVES to cuddle and play! She would do great in a home with other dogs that also like to play. She's non-aggressive towards cats, but she definitely wants to play with them. If you have a kitty that doesn't like a dog nose up the bum, she may not be a good fit. She's mouthy when excited, but doesn't bite, so kids just need to be aware of that and she should be fine with them. She's learned to sit on command, but she's stubborn, so "come" is not a command she enjoys obeying. She's got that little dog bark that just goes on and on when she is offended by being locked in her crate, or is certain an intruder is anywhere near, so an apartment would not be a great fit. She would do best in a fenced-in yard with a fence higher than 4 ft because she's a jumper and she climbs like a cat. She LOVES to sleep with people. If a people is sleeping nearby, she's sure to be on top of them! She is house trained, but she's still young, so she gets into trouble like eating or chewing on things she shouldn't. She likes to dig trenches and she's a powerful chewer for such a little dog! She's about a year old and roughly 25 lbs. She will be spayed February 16th and can go to her forever home after that date.

animal.description:
Oslo is definitely man's best friend! At 10 weeks old this handsome, roly poly Lab mix puppy already weighs 18 pounds, and we suspect he will be about 65 pounds when fully grown. Oslo's foster family tells us that he has a crazy and great personality, and is the sweetest and most loving dog they have ever met. He is playful and energetic, but also knows when it's time to calm down and relax with a nice belly rub and a nap - hopefully on someone's lap. He is happiest when he is with people, and is a world class snuggler. Oslo loves his toys and balls, and has a silly way of stretching all the way out on the rug by your feet to gnaw on his chew toys.

Curious and confident, Oslo has a twinkle in his eye and pep in his step as he bravely explores his surroundings. He is very friendly and enjoys meeting new people and other dogs, regardless of their size. Oslo is a smart little boy and is doing well with his potty and crate training. He definitely has opinions of his own, but is so sweet natured and easy going that he is easily redirected and brought back to focus. His enthusiasm for fun and games can sometimes get the better of him, but all is forgiven when you look into that beautiful little face and see the love in those cute eyes. Oslo will make a wonderful addition to any family, and will be a loving and devoted companion.


Thank you so much for your interest in adopting a dog from A New Chance Animal Rescue (https://anewchancear.org). We are a 501c3, tax deductible organization. ANCAR is a foster-based rescue, and we adopt within a 90 mile radius of Bedford Hills, NY.  You will find the adoption application here: (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-application/).  All fields on the application must be completed.
Please read about the adoption process (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-process/) so you'll know what to expect when you submit.   

Our dogs are in foster care and we do NOT have a shelter or boarding facility. AN APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED IN FULL AND APPROVED BEFORE A DOG CAN BE MET. This is a firm policy. Our busy volunteers are not able to respond to questions about the dog or dog meeting requests in the absence of an application.  We know these dogs very well because they are in foster care. Please read the profiles of the dog(s) you are interested in prior to submitting an application.  If there are specific requirements stated (ie: Fenced Yard or Canine Friend Required) these are included because they are vital to the happiness, health, safety and adoption success of that dog. 

We are only able to save as many dogs as we have foster homes (https://anewchancear.org/foster/faqs/) and resources for. We provide medical care including vaccinations, testing, deworming, spaying/neutering and microchipping before transporting our dogs. We provide all supplies, preventatives and any follow up vet care necessary while they are in foster care. These costs are high and the number of lives we can save is entirely dependent upon donations from people like you.  We do not receive funding from private foundations or government sources. If you can find room in your heart to help us, with any amount, we are truly grateful (https://anewchancear.org/help/donate/). We are a 501c3 organization, so all donations are tax-deductible. It is only through the kindness of supporters like you that we are 'changing lives...one tail at a time' by providing our dogs with 'A New Chance.' (https://anewchancear.org) 

Thanks so much.

animal.description:
I have an Adoption Pending and will be going home soon.  But I hope you will consider one of our other wonderful dogs in need.  Thank you!

Sweet Kelly was found running loose in a Louisiana Parish.  As stunning and loving as she is we were amazed that no one came to claim her at the shelter.  Oh, if only these dogs could tell us their stories... 

Kelly is a medium-sized girl weighing about 47 lbs.  She is estimated to be about 1-2 years-old and may be a Golden mix.  Whatever it is that went into her DNA, it surely produced one beautiful dog!  She came to our rescue as a shy dog, but has now warmed up as she receives attention and affection.  Her inner happiness has started to emerged and we are thrilled to see her wanting to frolic and play!  Presently, her activity is restricted as she completes her heartworm treatment.  But her cute personality is still showing through.   She has become a big fan of belly rubs and is becoming more comfortable each day. 

Kelly would do well with another dog in her new home or she can be the apple of her human's eye in a single pet home.  She walks pretty well on a leash and rode nicely in the car.  She is very sweet and is so gentle when taking treats from your hand.  In the care of a loving adopter, she will continue to blossom into a happy little bundle of fun. 

Kelly has been brought up-to-date on vaccinations, is spayed, micro-chipped, and is under treatment for heartworm. For the first year of adoption, she must be given the brand name Heartguard for her heartworm preventative.  After that, a generic may be considered.  Kelly is scheduled to come north from AL, to be directly adopted into her new forever home, mid February.

Rescued dogs come with a range of needs - from behavioral to emotional to medical.  When approved applicants adopt such dogs, they agree to continue the rehabilitation we have begun.        

If not yet approved for adoption, please visit our website to learn more and to submit an online application:     http://sunshinegoldenrescue.com/adoption-info1.html  

Please DO NOT use the ASK ABOUT button to contact us, about this dog, as that will delay our ability to respond to your inquiry.  Please direct any questions regarding your application status to:  ajpillinger@gmail.com   

Thank you!
 
ABOUT OUR RESCUE
Before being approved to adopt, all potential adopters will be required to complete our online application and participate in our pre-adoption review process. The process includes the completion of an online application, a reference from the applicants' vet, a phone interview, and a visit to the applicants' home.  The application process helps us determine what type of Golden would be best suited for the applicants' life style.  In some cases, the specific dog you are interested in may have found a home before this process is complete or further assessment may indicate that this dog is not the right match for your family.  We are frequently getting new Goldens in need of a home, so we encourage you to apply and complete the application process so that when the right dog comes along you will be ready. 

The information provided on each dog is based on the observations of our vets, volunteers, fosters, and when available, trainers. While we do our best to report any and all issues, SGRR does not make any guarantees as to the health or temperament of any dog. Dogs evolve differently in different environments and we cannot predict with any certainty how the dog you adopt will behave and adapt in your home.

SGRR ADOPTION FEES - Effective May 1, 2020  (subject to change)
  
  $750    Puppy - up to 6 months              
  $650    Young 6 months - 6 years            
  $550    Senior 7 - 9  years                       
  $450    Senior 10 years and older          
 
  $550    Young Special Needs                
  $400    Senior 7+ Special Needs                

$1000    Young Bonded Pair                   
  $900    Senior 7+ Bonded Pair         

A contract is signed on the day of adoption.  Under the terms of the contract, all adopters are required to bring their SGRR dog to a vet within 7 business days.  All dogs receive basic veterinary care prior to adoption.  However, if an adopter's vet identifies an illness that an adopter is not willing to treat, then the dog may be returned and a full refund would be provided. 

Most of our dogs are fostered in private homes.  We do not have a facility to visit.  We are committed to our dogs before, during, and after adoption! To this end, the rescue retains an interest in each dog and our dogs can never be surrendered, re-homed, or sold. Should an adopter no longer be able to keep their SGRR dog, SGRR must be notified so that we can take the dog back into rescue and place it into another home. We reserve the right to remove a dog at any time should we find the adopter is no longer providing proper care.  Adopters agree to follow up visits as needed.  

Please be a ray of light for this Sunshine dog and make a tax deductible donation toward medical care and other expenses.   Every cent of your generosity goes directly toward the care of a Sunshine dog.

Please visit our website at: http://sunshinegoldenrescue.com  to learn more about our rescue and to make a Donation to support Sunshine Golden Retriever Rescue.  

THANK YOU!

animal.description:
MEET SAM!
This poor baby was found by a couple in Braselton the day after Christmas. He was injured— limping and bleeding. According to the vet it appeared he had been attacked by multiple dogs. The vet cleaned him up, shaved him down and gave him his rabies shot. They estimate his age to be a year and a half and is mid-sized dog. Reminder...he has been completely shaved while healing - but Sam has a Border Collie coat of long, silky hair. Sam will be fully vetted while in our care - including neuter and micro-chip. Sam is precious and a lover! He gets along with most of the dogs he interacts with, he is in Haven's doggy day play everyday. Sam will need someone willing to spend a little time working with him (he's young) - he just has had no training of any kind - so he likes to jump on you, and he pulls on a leash. Just like 90% of all of our dogs ? The great part is - he's a nice and friendly dog! Interested in meeting him, please fill out our online adoption application and we will contact you to arrange a meet and greet.

animal.description:
Meet Abi! She’s an adorable (we think BOL) Bassett/Terrier mix. Whatever she is, she is adorable. She’s about 18 months old and weighs about 28-30 pounds. She is spayed, up to date on shots and on monthly heartworm preventative. Abi is also house trained and crate trained.

Abi was rescued from the side of the road and no one came forward so the finders have been caring for her and reached out to me for help finding her a furever home. She is very sweet but very strong but because of their age, they think she’d do best in a home with someone younger and better able to handle her energy and strength. They think Abi would do best in a home by herself. She’s a girl; she wants all the attention. She has done fine with the smaller dog in the home. They are fed separately and crated when no one is home. She does fine with the older grandchildren (8+ years old). She is fun loving and rambunctious and can knock over smaller two foots accidentally.

From Abi’s rescuer: Abi is a mixed breed I saved from traffic on the side of the road. I tried diligently to find her owners. Facebook, all pet websites, animal shelter, posters all around the location where she was, neighborhood websites, and door to door. After not having success with that I took her to the vet and got her shots, all tests, etc and she was very healthy. She was crate trained and basically house trained. She learned very quickly to ring the bell to go outside. She still loves her crate and sleeps there every night. At first she was very territorial about her food so she eats outside and sits for her food. I have a video of that. I decided to train her to be on a leash and to do the basic commands. She will sit, heel, come, come forward and turn, swing out and return to a sit beside me. She will stay for 10 minutes or more but is not so secure in that and sometimes moves. She’s a puppy still so easily distracted. She will go from sit to down and stay. She is 27-30 pounds of solid muscle when she runs thru the house she could easily cause me to tumble down. Her energy is not always non-stop, but she needs to play outside and fetch. She needs to walk around the block several times. She is very lovable and will sit beside me on the couch or on the back of the couch right by my head. She still chews a lot so I have many chew toys which she likes to hide. She is a great pet but too much energy and too heavy for 2 older people so we really want us to find her another home.

If you are interested in Abi, please complete our application.

http://bit.ly/4Paws1HeartDogAdoption

animal.description:
Angus McWigglebottom is a guy who truly lives up to his name. Talk sweetly to him, and his entire body sways side to side with excited wiggles! He's a big puppy who thinks he's a much smaller puppy, and will try to crawl into the best seat in the house... your lap! Angus will need an adopter who understands that puppies require some work and training to become well balanced adults. Angus will also need a home without small children, as he has been known to guard his food. To turn that into a positive, Angus is extremely treat motivated, so positive reinforcement training with treats should keep his interest and help him learn new skills and commands. He's a rough player with other dogs (think "wrestlemania"), so we are trying to find Angus a home where he is the only dog. With some more canine socialization, he may be able to have a friend in the future. Angus hasn't met a person he hasn't wanted to shower with love, he just needs to find his match!

 Primary Color: Brown Secondary Color: White Weight: 54lbs Age: 0yrs 11mths 1wks

animal.description:
Meet Luna! Luna is around 8 months old and 37lbs. She was brought into a rural Alabama shelter because she "got too big".  She has stunning eyes and a beautiful merle coat.  She likes other dogs and is friendly with people too. 
 Luna loves to be wherever her people are and is content doing whatever you want, whether that’s lounging on the couch or going for a hike outside. She has a calm house presence and is always thrilled to see her people whether you’ve been gone for an hour or less than a minute, she’ll be right there to greet you with her tail wagging. 
 She has wonderful manners, she doesn’t really jump up or get mouthy and she isn’t pushy when it comes to food. She enjoys chewing on bones and has no problem giving them up to you and will gladly take a belly rub or pets over any treat. Though you do need to put your shoes away so they don't become a dog chew.
 She’s doing wonderful with house training and is calm and quiet in her crate but isn’t really a fan. And will shred her blankets in the crate.
 She is a lovely little girl that just wants to be loved, some nice toys, a soft bed and tasty treats are a definite bonus though.

Interested in this sweet dog? Apply today at http://www.underdogpetrescue.org/dog-application

**Please note: Our animals live in foster homes throughout the Madison area. We do not have a shelter where animals are available for daily viewing. Applying is the first step in our process.**

Dogs from Underdog Pet Rescue come with the following medical care already provided:
Spay/Neuter
Rabies, Distemper, and Bordetella Vaccinations (as age appropriate-puppy adopters may need to cover some vaccine boosters)
Heartworm Test (for dogs over 6mo)
Microchip
Deworming
Heartworm and Flea/Tick Preventative
Any other necessary medical treatment as recommended by veterinarian

Our adult dog adoption fee is $300. Our puppy (under 5 mo) is $375. Our senior dog (over 8 yrs) is $250.

*Please note that all breeds noted are estimates or best guesses. We very rarely have information on our animals' actual breeds since they often come to the shelters we work with as strays*

animal.description:
Meet Rad! 

Rad was in a home in Georgia where he was found tied up by the waist to a tree. Animal control officers were called and obtained custody of him before he came to our campus. Even though Rad had a rough start, he is a super cool dog who absolutely loves life! He is very energetic and loves to run around with toys and other dogs. His ideal home would have a big yard with a solid fence to keep him safe (He is a jumper!). Rad would also do best in a home without small children. Rad is good on a leash and would like someone who would take him for walks and outings to dog friendly places. Rad loves to learn and explore. Unfortunately, his experience being left outside and then living in a kennel environment has not allowed him to learn to not have accidents inside. Rad needs someone who is patient and forgiving to help him get over this unfortunate habit. Rad is very sweet and playful. He is looking for a home that will offer him the love and patience he needs to develop appropriate habits. 
Please send us a message if you are interested in adopting this sweet boy!

animal.description:
This 1yr old Black Lab mix has some energy and doesn’t hold still long enough for pictures!! Half Pint came to us from an overcrowded shelter in Arkansas. I think he’s still a puppy as he has many puppy traits & I think he also has some growing to do yet too...

He is good with other dogs - very playful, unknown about cats, good with kids, strangers and all adults. He should be supervised around kids under 6yrs old as he can jump up and still play bite. He is very puppy like for 1yr old. He weighs about 35#.

Half Pint does fine in the kennel while you’re working or at school and for overnights. He does stir for a little bit before setting in & laying down. 

He likes to chew, so bones or durable toys are his favorite! He needs some training still: basic obedience, continued work on potty training (still some accidents - hence why I think he’s still a puppy) & he has very limited leash experience. 

He will need a patient and consistent home that can train him into the well rounded adult dog they want him to be!

Come meet this handsome boy today!

Adoption Fee: $450 (cash/card only) 

Foster to call: Jaime 651-324-1105 or Jaime3369@gmail.com

Due to the recommendations about the coronavirus, we are not able to have group adoption events at PetSmart.  We are, however, allowed to do individual adoptions so if you are interested in this pup/dog, please contact the foster listed above to set up a meeting.  We look forward to continuing to save dogs with you and will resume group adoptions as soon as we can.  Thank you for your patience and understanding.

Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home.  An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home.  Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home & truly become comfortable.  There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption; discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, & 3 months.  We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.   

Last Hope, Inc. is an all volunteer, foster based, no kill rescue! You can see almost all of our dogs on Saturdays from 11am - 3pm at Lakeville PetSmart (located by Hy-Vee just off 160th & Pilot Knob) & Burnsville Petsmart (located just off Hwy 35E & County Rd 42 by Chianti Grill).

Policies: You do not have to have a fence to adopt a dog from us, but some dogs will require a fence or acres to play, or an active family who will make sure the dog gets the exercise it needs to be happy.  Some dogs do not have the temperament that will do well with young children.   

The Adoption Fee is not enough to cover the vet bills. Sales tax of almost 7.25% is also included in the adoption fee that you see. Please consider donating to Last Hope to help us save these animals!

CAN YOU FOSTER? By taking a dog or puppies temporarily into your home and then coming to our adoption days to help find them homes, we can save more! If you’re interested, please email our dog coordinator: jaime3369@gmail.com and give us your contact information and what you would like to foster and someone will get back to you! You can also apply to be a foster home on our webpage! In the upper left hand corner there’s a drop down tab with the link for canine foster home. Just fill it out online & submit! We will get back to you as quick as we can.

animal.description:
Look at this cute little man!! Bear was found as a stray in Texas, at only 4 months old! Bear is likely a Beagle/Sherpherd mix. With almost any rescue though, breed is just a guess! Bear is only 4 months old, (still a baby!) and 25 lbs. He will likely be about 50lbs full grown. 

Bear’s floppy ears and squishy face are to die for! This poor little guy was found sitting in a puddle on mud in the pouring rain. He has since been with one of our Texas rescue partner’s fosters, living the dream! He is a typical, bouncy, silly puppy! 

With any rescue, moving from a shelter to a foster to an adoptive home can be very confusing. When an adopting family is sensitive to the challenges of change and acclimation for these dog's, the transition is far easier. A home with a very loving and nurturing family that understands that blossoming takes time would be perfect home for a rescue dog. Socialization, pure love and belly rubs is a gift to a dog that is undergoing a life change. Given the time and space, these dogs shine. 

Farfel's Rescue has found over time (we've rescued more than 3,000 dogs over 15 years of rescue) that families that attend level 1 group training classes or address individual challenges at home with one of our approved positive reinforcement/force free trainers keep their dogs for life. Dogs that do not get proper training and socialization have a much higher risk of developing behavioral problems. There is a bonding that occurs through the training process that can't be duplicated. It also teaches behaviors that enable a dog to go out into the world with excellent manners that create a very respectful relationship between dogs and their humans. It is for all these reasons that Farfel's isn't willing to adopt to a family that doesn't choose to create this training relationship. Farfel's is happy to provide a list of approved positive reinforcement/ force-free trainers in your area. 

Bear is up to date on his vaccines, and we have requested he be neutered prior to transport. If he is not neutered prior to transporting to Colorado, Farfel’s Rescue will cover all costs of his neuter. Neuter is required to finalize any adoption!

Bear is arriving on transport in Boulder on Wednesday 2/3/2021. Applications are currently being accepted for our wonderful pup. If interested in this gorgeous, very cuddly/sweet and loving best friend, please fill out an application completely at http://farfels.com/farfels-rescue/adoption-form/ and submit.

**PLEASE NOTE** If you're truly interested in adopting from us, please be sure to fill out our Farfel's Rescue adoption application found at the link above or at farfels.com. Adoption site applications such as Petfinder, Rescueme and Adoptapet don't provide enough information and therefore aren't useful. Our Farfel's application is the only initial tool that we have to determine a great match for this very deserving puppy. We're sorry, but in most cases, we're unable to get back to those that don't submit our Farfel's Rescue adoption application. Thanks very much for choosing rescue.

If you are interested in this dog please fill out an online application on our website:                          https://.barkdogfarm.rescuegroups.org/forms/ 

 
Please be sure all family members are in agreement to adopting and your family is ready to bring dog home now. 
Applicants must be at least 21 years old. 
A volunteer will be in touch to discuss your application and the dog to determine if it is a good match. Your vet and two references will be called.  A virtual home visit done. Once approved a meet and greet at the farm will take place.  If all are in agreement and the animal has received its NH health certificate an adoption contract will be signed and adoption fee paid.  
Adoption fees for dogs are $450. for adults over 12 months, $500 for puppies 12 months and younger.  Fees for seniors, special needs or harder to place dogs will be determined by our Board of Directors.
 All dogs will be altered when adoption is finalized, up to date on age appropriate core vaccines, negative for parasites, heart worm and lyme tested if 6 months or older, microchipped and have a current health certificate.  
Proof of a basic obedience course completed is part of our adoption contract within six months. 
Our descriptions are based on shelter evaluations, input from foster homes and interactions with our volunteers therefore are in no way a guarantee of temperment. 

! Please know we practice Covid-19 guidelines for mask wearing and social distancing.  Only approved applicants are allowed to meet our dogs outdoors at this time. Please email barkingdogfrm@gmail.com with any questions.

animal.description:
Meet Chelsea!

Hello new friends, I'm Chelsea. I'm about 10 years old, 15 pounds, and I don't hear anymore, so I like to keep my people in my sight when I can. I go potty outside as long as you get me out when I let you know I have to go. You can't wait until a commercial comes on when you're watching your favorite show, so I hope your remote has a pause button. I get along with respectful kids, who are a bit older so they don't torment me, cats, and even other dogs. I don't really play with others, but I can live peacefully with just about any dog. I'm not fond of being in a crate, but once I know I'm going to be in there because you have to leave, I just go to sleep until you come home and let me out. 

Speaking of sleeping, that's how I spend most of my days now that I'm a bit older. But, let me tell you, while I'm awake I have a habit of eating anything on the floor, so please make sure it's all picked up for me when you bring me home. That's another reason I probably shouldn't live with really little kids, I suppose. I would make a perfect lap dog for someone, and I promise to keep you warm on those chilly winter nights. I do have a fuzzy raccoon toy that I enjoy playing with for a few minutes at a time, and I like to think that I'm pretty cute while I do! At night my foster mom let's me sleep with her, and she lifts me up on her bed since I can't get up there on my own. Hopefully soon I'll be sleeping in bed with you!

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

animal.description:
Meet Snuggles!! She’s a 1 year old Pointer/Pit mix that came to us from an overcrowded shelter in Arkansas. She’s 45# of love & sweetness and is full grown.

Snuggles got her name because she LOVES to snuggle (but isn’t pushy). There’s no air gap between her and her person. She has been lacking human attention before coming to rescue & now she just can’t get enough! She loves to just hang out with you on the couch for quiet evenings watching your favorite tv marathons or a movie. 

She is good in her kennel (crate trained) when you’re at work/school and for overnights. Snuggles does really well with her 2 resident dog friends. Unknown about cats. She is great with all age kids. Quiet girl; not a barker.

Snuggles is a gentle dog, mellow & just loves endlessly. She would love a home where affection never gets old and maybe multiple people in the home to give it to her!

Snuggles loves long walks and does very well on a leash. She doesn’t have any aggression issues (food or leash), no anxiety (even though she’d love to be glued to your hip, but she can wait while you’re away). 

So, if you’re looking for that perfect, mellow & affectionate dog to join your family, look no further than Snuggles! She can’t wait to meet you so contact her foster mom today! 

Foster to call/text: 
Amy 651-815-3423

Adoption Fee: $350 (cash/card only)

Due to the recommendations about the coronavirus, we are not able to have group adoption events at PetSmart.  We are, however, allowed to do individual adoptions so if you are interested in this pup/dog, please contact the foster listed above to set up a meeting.  We look forward to continuing to save dogs with you and will resume group adoptions as soon as we can.  Thank you for your patience and understanding.

Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home.  An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home.  Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home & truly become comfortable.  There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption; discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, & 3 months.  We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.   

Last Hope, Inc. is an all volunteer, foster based, no kill rescue! You can see almost all of our dogs on Saturdays from 11am - 3pm at Lakeville PetSmart (located by Hy-Vee just off 160th & Pilot Knob) & Burnsville Petsmart (located just off Hwy 35E & County Rd 42 by Chianti Grill).

Policies: You do not have to have a fence to adopt a dog from us, but some dogs will require a fence or acres to play, or an active family who will make sure the dog gets the exercise it needs to be happy.  Some dogs do not have the temperament that will do well with young children.   

The Adoption Fee is not enough to cover the vet bills. Sales tax of almost 7.25% is also included in the adoption fee that you see. Please consider donating to Last Hope to help us save these animals!

CAN YOU FOSTER? By taking a dog or puppies temporarily into your home and then coming to our adoption days to help find them homes, we can save more! If you’re interested, please email our dog coordinator: jaime3369@gmail.com and give us your contact information and what you would like to foster and someone will get back to you! You can also apply to be a foster home on our webpage! In the upper left hand corner there’s a drop down tab with the link for canine foster home. Just fill it out online & submit! We will get back to you as quick as we can.

animal.description:
Hi I’m Hannah! I’m an almost 1 old super shepherd mix. The breed is a guess by the vet.

“Hannah is super affectionate and sweet.  She learned so much and settled in wonderfully in the short time that she’s been with us and is going to be a great dog!

Hannah does great with dogs, kids snd cats but needs lots of slow introductions. She would be better with older children because she gets too excited and has knocked them over.

Has a weak back left leg healing from FHO surgery . She will need PT and strengthening exercises - and can’t do full exercise yet. May never heal properly and may always have a limp

Hannah was originally found as a stray in Mississippi. Therefore her age and breed are a COMPLETE mystery to us, the MS rescue we work with, and both the MS vet and our NH vet. We avoid making any guesses. We have to label them as some breed on petfinder, so please take this breed as a compete guess (guess by 2 licensed vets). 

Hannah is spayed, microchipped, up to date on vaccines (distemper, parvo, boardatella, and rabies), and has 2 recent health exams. Hannah goes home with a VT state health certificate which certifies by a legal veterinarian that they are healthy at the time of adoption. Hannah has been dewormed and has 2 negative fecals at the time of adoption(1 prior to entering NH/VT, and another negative fecal before adoption.) Hannah is on monthly heartworm preventative and flea and tick preventative.  

Hannah has been getting lots of socialization with dogs, kids and cats.  

Hannah’s adoption fee is $500. The fee is based on our cost to spay/neuter, vet transport, deworm, “get healthy”, re-check their health at our NH vet. 100% of the fee goes to our non profit rescue and helps cover the cost of the puppy and helps the next puppy in need. 

Due to limited resources we are only responding to people who fill out our adoption application 

To apply to adopt:  https://www.secondchanceranchrescue.com/apply-to-adopt

Shannon is four years old, and she was brought to The Fuzzy Pet Foundation - (TFPF) when her family could no longer care for her. They had purchased her as a puppy from a breeder in South Korea. She is a purebred, black English Labrador Retriever currently being fostered in Long Beach, CA.

Shannon can be shy at first, but she is extremely loving and well-trained. Although she previously lived in a home with teenagers, she would do best in an adult-only home without a ton of noise and commotion. She loves her walks and gets attached to her caregivers quickly.  She knows how to sit and shake. She is a loyal, loving girl. 

Shannon has a clean bill of health. She is spayed, microchipped, and current on vaccines. She also has up-to-date blood work and recently underwent prophylactic gastropexy (a surgical procedure to prevent bloat that is common in large-breed dogs).  

TFPF is looking for a stable, loving family for Shannon. We are hoping to find an adopter who is experienced with the Lab breed and who has the time and resources to care for her for life.

animal.description:
We found Nemo, and Dory too! 

This dynamic duo have embraced the "just keep swimming" motto! Nemo and Dory are both very happy and friendly mutts! Dory is round and her tail is always wagging! She makes the cutest little snorty noises. Nemo is a peppy, friendly and curious, guy who is always up for anything. These two are instant mood boosters and will make their new family entertained and smiling! Besides, whats better than a new mutt, than 2! 

* HERE'S WHAT THEIR FOSTER HAS TO SAY! *

Dory and Nemo are the sweetest senior pups! They are mellow, easygoing, and independent. They are both motivated by love pets, hugs, kisses, and praises vs treats. They both love to be held and petted. They are always so happy and cheerful with their tails wagging very fast when I talk to them and take them out for short walks or hanging out in our backyard! They get along well with our 3 dogs and enjoy being part of a pack.

Dory is low maintenance and loves to cuddle on the couch. She is always so happy to play with Nemo in the backyard and snuggle at night together even though they both have their own bed next to the another. However, they end up on the same bed snuggling during the night and in the morning, I wake up to the cutest snuggle bunnies! Dory is unable to see but her hearing is enhanced and she follows my voice with ease. She's unaffected by her seeing impairment and she is not afraid of the unknown elements. In fact, she loves to explore!

Nemo is very interactive. He loves being my helper in the kitchen and loves following me throughout the day around the house or his eyes are following me around the room from his booster seat. animal.description:
Kyle is a 1yr old, 34# Heeler mix that came to us from an overcrowded shelter in Oklahoma. 

He is good with other dogs per the sending shelter, but the foster home doesn’t have other dogs. He sees other dogs during walks and does fine & did just fine with everyone on the transport. Unknown about cats.

Kyle LOVES people and would be good with older kids.  He can get very excited and jumpy when meeting nee friends and could scratch/knock over a small child unintentionally. Also, he is very mouthy when he plays & a young child make think he’s trying to bite.

Kyle isn’t a barker. As far as being kenneled: he will go into the kennel with a treat; but he has VERY high separation anxiety (he hasn’t has good kennel experiences prior to coming into rescue). He would do best in a home where someone is around most/all of the time so he doesn’t have to be kenneled or alone for long periods. The anxiety might lessen over time as he get more situated into his home and with his high energy needs being met on a regular basis. He does sleep in his kennel, in our room at night - since we are in the room he does ok & he’s also there when we leave, but he gets anxious when we leave. 

Kyle is still adjusting to home life vs being stuck in a kennel in a shelter. He did have a few pee accidents the first 2 days in foster care, but not poop accidents - he whines to go outside for those. Kyle did get an upset tummy from starting a quality food once in rescue, so swapping foods should be kept minimal to avoid diarrhea. No food aggression issues.

He walks fine one a leash but does pull a bit when he sees another dog, rabbit, squirrel or human. He’s excited to see them!

Kyle is a smart dog, but it’s obvious that nobody’s taken the time to train him as he doesn’t know any basic obedience commands just yet. Foster home is working on SIT, COME and DOWN. 

Kyle does like to chew, so giving him lots of the proper items to chew on like bones and power chewer toys will help keep him from chewing your shoes/boots and other plastic items or things in his crate. He is learning these items are not chew toys & what HIS toys are. He does also put his front paws on the table and would take some food if it was close enough to the edge. He is learning that this is not ok to do. Life is so different in a home vs 4 concrete walls or running free as a stray, but he’s adjusting and learning, it just takes time. This smart boy is catching on quick with consistent foster parents!

Kyle likes to get up on the comfy couch and bed (they’re sooo soft!), but this is just something that can be taught to stay off of if you don’t allow that in your home. 

Heeler mixes tend to be higher energy & need an active family, older kids to play and wear them out, another dog in their home or maybe someone in the home that runs/hikes on a regular basis to get the exercise they crave. He could probably easily jump a 4’ fence (he’s athletic) and would make a good agility or frisbee dog if you’re interested in that!

Kyle is a friendly, sweet and energetic dog who just needs some training, consistency and stability in his life. Could you be the one to put all the pieces together for this adorable guy?  

Adoption Fee: $350 (cash/card only) 

Kyle is with a new foster with our rescue so please contact our Dog Coordinator for more information: 

Jaime 651-324-1105 or Jaime3369@gmail.com

Due to the recommendations about the coronavirus, we are not able to have group adoption events at PetSmart.  We are, however, allowed to do individual adoptions so if you are interested in this pup/dog, please contact the foster listed above to set up a meeting.  We look forward to continuing to save dogs with you and will resume group adoptions as soon as we can.  Thank you for your patience and understanding.

Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home.  An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home.  Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home & truly become comfortable.  There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption; discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, & 3 months.  We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.   

Last Hope, Inc. is an all volunteer, foster based, no kill rescue! You can see almost all of our dogs on Saturdays from 11am - 3pm at Lakeville PetSmart (located by Hy-Vee just off 160th & Pilot Knob) & Burnsville Petsmart (located just off Hwy 35E & County Rd 42 by Chianti Grill).

Policies: You do not have to have a fence to adopt a dog from us, but some dogs will require a fence or acres to play, or an active family who will make sure the dog gets the exercise it needs to be happy.  Some dogs do not have the temperament that will do well with young children.   

The Adoption Fee is not enough to cover the vet bills. Sales tax of almost 7.25% is also included in the adoption fee that you see. Please consider donating to Last Hope to help us save these animals!

CAN YOU FOSTER? By taking a dog or puppies temporarily into your home and then coming to our adoption days to help find them homes, we can save more! If you’re interested, please email our dog coordinator: jaime3369@gmail.com and give us your contact information and what you would like to foster and someone will get back to you! You can also apply to be a foster home on our webpage! In the upper left hand corner there’s a drop down tab with the link for canine foster home. Just fill it out online & submit! We will get back to you as quick as we can.

animal.description:
Brody is two years of age and had been dealt a bad hand in life.  His former owner not just neglected and starved him but abandoned him in the middle of the desert.  The local animal shelter found Brody whimpering in the desert, carrying around a toy in his mouth.  They traced Brody's owner via his microchip, and the owner told them, "I don't want the dog anymore!"

At The Fuzzy Pet Foundation - (TFPF), Brody has been getting plenty of love and attention.  His teeth were nicely polished, and he has been gaining back his weight.  We are helping Brody to open up more to humans as he is understandably hurt and traumatized.

Brody is a very loving boy who would do best in an adult-only home.  He is afraid of certain men. While he will tolerate other dogs, he prefers to be the only pet, too.  He thrives on routine and would love a guardian who spends a lot of time inside the home.  Brody gets attached to people very fast -- he follows around our volunteers, whimpers to let us know he is feeling insecure or scared.  He LOVES to go on walks and will carry around his toy everywhere he goes!

animal.description:
Sugar is a 9 year old Maltese and spent her entire life as a breeding machine in a puppy mill. As a result she is fearful of humans, terrified of strangers, frightened by loud noises and quick movements. She has however, come a long way towards socialization. Sugar knows her name. That being said she is still working on coming when she's called.

Sugar is a very smart little girl which might be a reason why she can be stubborn. She'll look at you when you call her name but will only come to you if it suits her. Sugar is very treat motivated. If she knows you have a treat she will come over right away every time you call her. 

Sugar is working on her potty training. Again, here's where her stubborn streak shows. She knows she's supposed to potty outside but if it's too cold, too wet, too sunny, too dark, too whatever she will choose to potty inside. She knows what a pee pad is for and will use them if she's in the mood. Otherwise she will either pee right next to the pad or pee wherever the mood strikes her. 

Sugar LOVES toys and will hoard them by loading them in her crate. This brings me to another subject. The crate. Because Sugar was a mill dog she is never locked in her crate. Being locked in a crate gives Sugar great anxiety and she will bark incessantly. The door is always open allowing her to come and go as she pleases.  

Crate potty training is not an option. Because Sugar lived  24/7 in a cage she has no problem going potty in her crate and then walking, rolling and laying in the mess. Because of anxiety and stress of being kenneled Sugar will shred a pee pad placed in the crate with her. Sugar has tasted freedom and refuses to give it up. 

Sugar knows the doggie doors and loves going in and outside as she pleases during the day. She is living with multiple dogs of multiple sizes and gets along well with them all. 
I have no idea how she would get along with cats or other pets.

If it seems like I'm showing Sugar in a bad light that is not my intention. I just want anyone interested in adopting Sugar to understand she is not a normal dog with normal responses to normal situations. Sugar is a puppy mill survivor and as such she will need extra patience, extra love and extra time to decompress and open up. She will need someone who is home more often than not.  She needs someone who will allow her to remain unkenneled if left alone.

Because of her fear and small size Sugar needs a home with no small children and no medium or large dogs.  . 

Sugar is a flight risk so she needs a yard with a physical fence. ABSOLUTELY NO ELECTRIC FENCES! 

Because I will take Sugar back if the placement doesn't work out only homes within a 100 mile radius of Rockford IL will be considered. 
If you can meet all of the requirements above and feel you would like to adopt Sugar go to www.tinypawssmalldogrescue.org and fill out an online adoption application. Sugar's adoption fee is $350.00


Any questions, please contact my foster mom at :  kmehalko@att.net

animal.description:
There are so many lilies for a gardener to enjoy. There are Asiatic, Oriental, Calla, and Lilly of the Valley, just to name a few. But we prefer this canine variety. Lilly is a 3-year-old 52lb female Hound/Boxer mix. She is spayed, vaccinated and microchipped. She is crate-trained and nearly housetrained. She is learning to walk on leash with the aid of a prong-collar and she wears a backpack, too. She knows all her basic commands.

Lilly is affectionate but shy, playful and puppy-like, eager to please and, highly food-motivated. You could say that her fondness of food is both a problem and a solution . . .

Lilly is learning “house-manners.” She has a few habits that her people are working to curb, including: counter-surfing, garbage-eating (indoors) and digging (outdoors). But, an ounce of prevention is also worth a pound of cure. So, Lilly isn’t left unsupervised and food isn’t left out. Lilly’s finer qualities include playing well with submissive dogs and getting along with children—although with as much energy as she has, she’d pair much better with a teenager in need of a running partner than a youngster with no dog-sense. And, while looks aren’t everything, Lilly is a striking girl with a white body and a bridle head divided by a white stripe. We think she’ll win you over given half a chance.

To adopt, please submit an application at this link: http://form.jotform.com/form/11880935459 or visit www.pottersangelsrescue.org to view additional adoptable dogs and for more information. Adoption fees apply and vary by age:

animal.description: Hi! My name is Coco! I was rescued in Georgia before arriving at the Big Dog Ranch Rescue. I'm a young puppy with lots of energy and spunk! I love to run around and play! I'm friendly and happy and just want to get to know you. Aside from having tons of energy, sometimes I can be loud, as I don't know how to control my barking yet. animal.description: Hi! My name is Donovan! I was rescued by an animal shelter in Georgia before arriving at the Big Dog Ranch Rescue. I am a staff favorite here at the ranch, probably because I'm so sweet and well-behaved. I love to play with other dogs, regardless of their size. I think I would make an excellent family pet, particularly in a home with young children. I do appear to have a prey drive, and wouldn't be very happy in a home with feline companions. I'd be a great pick for a first-time dog owner, as long as you have some land for me to run around on! Aside from a big backyard, a busy home life would be nice, as I like to be involved in as many things as possible, all the time. I'm super friendly with everyone that I meet and may even be the type of pup that you want to bring out and about with you as you do your daily activities. I could benefit from some further obedience training, as well as some help with leash-walking, but I do appear to be mostly potty-trained already. I do love to go on long walks, play a rousing game of fetch, or snuggle up on the couch next to someone that truly loves me!
